{"title_page": "Lullwater (band)", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n{{Notability|Music|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = Lullwater\n| image           = Lullwater performing Live Left to right- Roy Beatty, John Strickland, Joe Wilson, Daniel Binnie.jpg\n| image_upright   = 1.15\n| landscape       = yes\n| alt             = Photo of Lullwater, a band from Athens, GA\n| caption         = Lullwater performing live (left to right- Roy Beatty, John Strickland, Joe Wilson, Daniel Binnie)\n| background      = group_or_band\n| origin          = [[Athens, Georgia]], U.S.\n| genre           = {{Flatlist|\n* [[Hard rock]]\n* [[alternative rock]]\n* [[post-grunge]]\n* [[Grunge]]\n}}\n| years_active    = 2007\u2013Present\n| label           = {{Flatlist|\n* Independent Artist\n}}\n| associated_acts = {{Flatlist|\n* Enochian\n* Joe Wilson Music\n}}\n| website         = {{URL|lullwatermusic.com}}\n| current_members = \n* [[John Strickland]]\n* [[Joe Wilson]]\n* [[Roy Beatty]]\n* [[Daniel Binnie]]\n| past_members    = \n* [[Phil Bush]]\n* [[Nick Thomas]]\n* [[Brett Strickland]]\n}}\n'''Lullwater''' is a [[rock (genre)|rock]] band formed in [[Athens, Georgia]] in 2007. The music group is known for its influences in the Seattle [[Grunge]] Sound and 80's hard rock.  Formed by John Strickland (lead vocals, rhythm guitar), Lullwater also includes Roy Beatty (bass), Joseph Wilson (drums) and Daniel Binnie (guitar). The band released their debut album, \u201cLullwater\u201d, on September 17, 2013<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://screamermagazine.com/interviews/done-lullwater-athens-georgia-delivers/|title=LULLWATER - Athens, Georgia Delivers Again|date=August 27, 2014|website=Screamer Magazine}}</ref> and toured to support that album.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://betweenthenotes.blog/2014/10/23/interview-with-lullwater/|title=Interview with Lullwater|date=October 23, 2014}}</ref> The band was named from the street that their original drummer lived on in Athens.  Their band practice house was on Lullwater Road in Athens.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.last.fm/music/Lullwater|title=Lullwater music, videos, stats, and photos|website=Last.fm}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===2007 \u2013 2011: Early days of the band and lineup changes===\nLullwater is brought together by John Strickland.  He completed the band's lineup by using Brett Strickland on lead guitar.  Drum duties were handled by Nick Thomas.  Phil Bush was the bass player. In 2009, Roy Beatty replaced Phil Bush as Lullwater's bass player.  In 2011, drummer Nick Thomas left the band and was replaced by Joseph Wilson from Savannah, GA, former dummer for Wormsloew.\n\n===2012 \u2013 2014: first album release===\nWith its new lineup, Lullwater began playing more clubs and touring.  In 2013, Lullwater recorded their first album at [[London Bridge Studio]] in Seattle, WA.<ref name=\"auto\"/>  Lullwater's self-titled album \u201cLullwater\u201d, released on September 17, 2013, pays homage to the grunge bands of the early 1990s who influenced their sound. The album was recorded on tape at London Bridge Studios in Seattle, WA and produced by Jonathan Plum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/noisetrade/music/lullwater|title=Lullwater Albums :: NoiseTrade :: Paste Magazine|website=www.pastemagazine.com}}</ref>  To promote \u201cLullwater\u201d, the band toured for 10 months following the release of the album, opening for [[Passafire]], [[Ra (American band)|RA]], Adakin, Ryan White and [[Flyleaf (band)|Flyleaf]]. Following the release of their self-titled album \"Lullwater\", the single \"Albatross\" received heavy rotation on [[Octane (Sirius XM)|SiriusXM Radio's Octane Channel]] channel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rockallphotography.com/?p=24405|title=Lullwater \u2013 Featured on SirusXM radio Octane Channel|first=Theresa|last=Patrick|date=September 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2015 \u2013 2016: second album release and new member===\nWhile touring, the band began writing new songs for the next album.  Lullwater chose to record their second album at [[Sonic Ranch]] in El Paso, TX.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://crypticrock.com/lullwater-revival-album-review/|title=Lullwater \u2013 Revival (Album Review)|first=Alexis|last=Coleman|date=December 28, 2015}}</ref> The result was \u201cRevival\u201d, a 12-track album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.getitonvinyl.com/lullwater-revival/|title=Album Review: Lullwater \"Revival\"|date=October 14, 2015}}</ref>  After the recording of \u201cRevival\u201d, Daniel Binnie replaced Brett Strickland on lead guitar. Following the release of \u201cRevival\u201d, Lullwater toured for 12 months to support the album, opening for [[Amaranthe]]  , [[Butcher Babies]], Another Lost Year, Temple Agents, [[Theory of a Deadman]] and [[Candlebox]] until the end of 2016.\n\n===2017 \u2013 present:  touring and a third album===\nLullwater continued to tour in 2017, 2018 and 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shockwavemagazine.com/another-lost-year-announce-tour-with-never-say-die-and-lullwater-promote-new-website/|title=Another Lost Year Announce Tour with Never Say Die and Lullwater; Promote New Website|date=February 3, 2017}}</ref> In December 2017, Lullwater moved into Marigny Studios in New Orleans, LA to record their next album, \u201cVoodoo\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rockallphotography.com/?p=27744|title=Lullwater ready to unleash the magic of Voodoo to the world|first=Shawn|last=Wiseman|date=February 17, 2019}}</ref> Jacob Herrmann from Sweden was the producer/engineer for \u201cVoodoo\u201d along with Justin Davis.  Voodoo was finally released on February 22, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rockdocumented.com/2019/02/08/album-review-lullwater-voodoo/|title=LULLWATER RELEASE VOODOO|date=February 8, 2019}}</ref>  The song Dark Divided off of \"Voodoo\" was listed in The Top 100 Hard Rock Songs of 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://hardrockdaddy.com/2020/01/05/top-100-hard-rock-songs-of-2019/|title=Top 100 Hard Rock Songs of 2019|last=AW|date=January 5, 2020}}</ref> I'm Music Magazine included Lullwater's \u201cVoodoo\u201d among their top 28 Albums of 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://im-musicmagazine.com/f/28-best-albums-of-2019?fbclid=IwAR0TleZYhLJs0-uzDqdegY1BPhIJN4IYBU3vfKMCkZpVOdz4ituVCDiQVuU|title=Top 28 Best Albums from 2019|website=www.im-musicmagazine.com/}}</ref> Dark Divided from \u201cVoodoo\u201d hit number 4 on the Foundations Secondary Market Rock Chart and made it to the most added at [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] Mainstream Rock indicator on October 5, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/rock-songs/2019-10-05 |title=Lullwater's Dark Divided reaches number 4 on Billboards Mainstream Rock Indicator|website=www.billboard.com/|date=October 1, 2019}}</ref> Tours to support \u201cVoodoo\u201d followed while opening for Another Lost Year, [[Gin Blossoms]], [[Collective Soul]], [[Candlebox]], Never Say Die, [[Daughtry (band)|Daughtry]], Kirra, Blacktop Mojo,  [[Powerman 5000]], [[Sevendust]] and [[Tremonti (band)|Tremonti]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blabbermouth.net/news/sevendust-announces-early-2019-u-s-tour-with-tremonti/|title=SEVENDUST Announces Early 2019 U.S. Tour With TREMONTI; BLABBERMOUTH.NET Presale Available|date=November 12, 2018|website=BLABBERMOUTH.NET}}</ref>  Sapphire Bullets ranked Lullwater's Voodoo album as one of the top 50 albums in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sapphirebulletsofpurelove.blogspot.com/?m=1/|title=Lullwater \u2013 Sapphire Bullet's Top Albums of 2019|first=Luke|last=Dunmore|date=December 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n*\u201cLullwater\u201d  (2013)  Released on September 17, 2013\n*\u201cRevival\u201d   (2015)    Released October 23, 2015\n*\u201cVoodoo\u201d   (2019)   Released February 22, 2019\n[[File:Cover of Lullwater, released in 2013.jpg|thumb|Cover of Lullwater, released in 2013]]\n[[File:Revival Cover, released in 2015.jpg|thumb|Revival Cover, released in 2015]]\n[[File:Voodoo Cover, released in 2019.jpg|thumb|Voodoo Cover, released in 2019]]\n\n==Band members==\n'''Current Members'''<br> \n                                                                                                                                                    \n*John Strickland:  Lead vocals and rhythm guitar\n*Joseph Wilson: drums and vocals\n*Roy Beatty: bass and vocals\n*Daniel Binnie:  lead guitar\n\n===Past members===\n*Phil Bush\n*Nick Thomas\n*Brett Strickland\n\n===Instruments===\n*John Strickland:  [[Gibson Les Paul]]\n*Joseph Wilson:  [[Pearl Drums]] / [[Avedis Zildjian Company|Zildjian Cymballs]]\n*Roy Beatty:  [[Dingwall Designer Guitars|Dingwall Guitars]]\n*Daniel Binnie:   [[Gibson Les Paul]]\n\n===Timeline===\n\n{{#tag:timeline\n|ImageSize = width:600 height:auto barincrement:25\nPlotArea   = left:120 bottom:100 top:10 right:10\nAlignbars  = justify\nDateFormat = dd/mm/yyyy\nPeriod     = from:01/01/2007 till:{{#time:d/m/Y}}\nTimeAxis   = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\nLegend     = orientation:vertical position:bottom columns:1\nScaleMajor = increment:2 start:2007\nScaleMinor = increment:1 start:2007\n\nColors = \n id:vocals   value:red       legend:Lead_vocals\n id:guitar   value:green     legend:Guitar\n id:keys     value:purple    legend:Keyboards\n id:bass     value:blue      legend:Bass_guitar\n id:drums    value:orange    legend:Drums\n id:backing  value:pink      legend:Backing_vocals\n id:perc     value:claret    legend:Percussion\n id:album    value:black     legend:Studio_album\n id:bs value:gray(0.1)\n\nLineData =\n layer:back\n color:album\n at:29/12/2013\n at:11/10/2015\n at:22/02/2019\n\nBarData =\n\n bar:JS text:\"John Strickland\"\n bar:BS text:\"Brett Strickland\"\n bar:PB text:\"Phil Bush\"\n bar:NT text:\"Nick Thomas\"\n bar:RB text:\"Roy Beatty\"\n bar:JW text:\"Joseph Wilson\"\n bar:DB text:\"Daniel Binnie\"\n\nPlotData =\n\n bar:JS from:start till:end color:vocals width:13\n bar:JS from:start till:end color:guitar width:3\n\n bar:BS from:start till:22/07/2016 color:guitar width:13\n\n bar:PB from:start till:01/01/2009 color:bass width:13\n\n bar:NT from:start till:01/01/2011 color:drums width:13\n\n bar:RB from:01/01/2009 till:end color:bass width:13\n bar:RB from:01/01/2009 till:end color:backing width:3\n\n bar:JW from:01/01/2011 till:end color:perc width:13\n bar:JW from:01/01/2011 till:end color:drums width:8\n bar:JW from:01/01/2011 till:end color:backing width:3\n\n bar:DB from:22/07/2016 till:end color:guitar width:13\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n\n[[Category:Grunge musical groups]]\n[[Category:American post-grunge musical groups]]\n[[Category:Rock music groups from Georgia (U.S. state]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n{{Notability|Music|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = Lullwater\n| image           = Lullwater performing Live Left to right- Roy Beatty, John Strickland, Joe Wilson, Daniel Binnie.jpg\n| image_upright   = 1.15\n| landscape       = yes\n| alt             = Photo of Lullwater, a band from Athens, GA\n| caption         = Lullwater performing live (left to right- Roy Beatty, John Strickland, Joe Wilson, Daniel Binnie)\n| background      = group_or_band\n| origin          = [[Athens, Georgia]], U.S.\n| genre           = {{Flatlist|\n* [[Hard rock]]\n* [[alternative rock]]\n* [[post-grunge]]\n* [[Grunge]]\n}}\n| years_active    = 2007\u2013Present\n| label           = {{Flatlist|\n* Independent Artist\n}}\n| associated_acts = {{Flatlist|\n* Enochian\n* Joe Wilson Music\n}}\n| website         = {{URL|lullwatermusic.com}}\n| current_members = \n* [[John Strickland]]\n* [[Joe Wilson]]\n* [[Roy Beatty]]\n* [[Daniel Binnie]]\n| past_members    = \n* [[Phil Bush]]\n* [[Nick Thomas]]\n* [[Brett Strickland]]\n}}\n'''Lullwater''' is a [[rock (genre)|rock]] band formed in [[Athens, Georgia]] in 2007. The music group is known for its influences in the Seattle [[Grunge]] Sound and 80's hard rock.  Formed by John Strickland (lead vocals, rhythm guitar), Lullwater also includes Roy Beatty (bass), Joseph Wilson (drums) and Daniel Binnie (guitar). The band released their debut album, \u201cLullwater\u201d, on September 17, 2013<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://screamermagazine.com/interviews/done-lullwater-athens-georgia-delivers/|title=LULLWATER - Athens, Georgia Delivers Again|date=August 27, 2014|website=Screamer Magazine}}</ref> and toured to support that album.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://betweenthenotes.blog/2014/10/23/interview-with-lullwater/|title=Interview with Lullwater|date=October 23, 2014}}</ref> The band was named from the street that their original drummer lived on in Athens.  Their band practice house was on Lullwater Road in Athens.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.last.fm/music/Lullwater|title=Lullwater music, videos, stats, and photos|website=Last.fm}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===2007 \u2013 2011: Early days of the band and lineup changes===\nLullwater is brought together by John Strickland.  He completed the band's lineup by using Brett Strickland on lead guitar.  Drum duties were handled by Nick Thomas.  Phil Bush was the bass player. In 2009, Roy Beatty replaced Phil Bush as Lullwater's bass player.  In 2011, drummer Nick Thomas left the band and was replaced by Joseph Wilson from Savannah, GA, former dummer for Wormsloew.\n\n===2012 \u2013 2014: first album release===\nWith its new lineup, Lullwater began playing more clubs and touring.  In 2013, Lullwater recorded their first album at [[London Bridge Studio]] in Seattle, WA.<ref name=\"auto\"/>  Lullwater's self-titled album \u201cLullwater\u201d, released on September 17, 2013, pays homage to the grunge bands of the early 1990s who influenced their sound. The album was recorded on tape at London Bridge Studios in Seattle, WA and produced by Jonathan Plum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/noisetrade/music/lullwater|title=Lullwater Albums :: NoiseTrade :: Paste Magazine|website=www.pastemagazine.com}}</ref>  To promote \u201cLullwater\u201d, the band toured for 10 months following the release of the album, opening for [[Passafire]], [[Ra (American band)|RA]], Adakin, Ryan White and [[Flyleaf (band)|Flyleaf]]. Following the release of their self-titled album \"Lullwater\", the single \"Albatross\" received heavy rotation on [[Octane (Sirius XM)|SiriusXM Radio's Octane Channel]] channel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rockallphotography.com/?p=24405|title=Lullwater \u2013 Featured on SirusXM radio Octane Channel|first=Theresa|last=Patrick|date=September 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2015 \u2013 2016: second album release and new member===\nWhile touring, the band began writing new songs for the next album.  Lullwater chose to record their second album at [[Sonic Ranch]] in El Paso, TX.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://crypticrock.com/lullwater-revival-album-review/|title=Lullwater \u2013 Revival (Album Review)|first=Alexis|last=Coleman|date=December 28, 2015}}</ref> The result was \u201cRevival\u201d, a 12-track album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.getitonvinyl.com/lullwater-revival/|title=Album Review: Lullwater \"Revival\"|date=October 14, 2015}}</ref>  After the recording of \u201cRevival\u201d, Daniel Binnie replaced Brett Strickland on lead guitar. Following the release of \u201cRevival\u201d, Lullwater toured for 12 months to support the album, opening for [[Amaranthe]]  , [[Butcher Babies]], Another Lost Year, Temple Agents, [[Theory of a Deadman]] and [[Candlebox]] until the end of 2016.\n\n===2017 \u2013 present:  touring and a third album===\nLullwater continued to tour in 2017, 2018 and 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shockwavemagazine.com/another-lost-year-announce-tour-with-never-say-die-and-lullwater-promote-new-website/|title=Another Lost Year Announce Tour with Never Say Die and Lullwater; Promote New Website|date=February 3, 2017}}</ref> In December 2017, Lullwater moved into Marigny Studios in New Orleans, LA to record their next album, \u201cVoodoo\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rockallphotography.com/?p=27744|title=Lullwater ready to unleash the magic of Voodoo to the world|first=Shawn|last=Wiseman|date=February 17, 2019}}</ref> Jacob Herrmann from Sweden was the producer/engineer for \u201cVoodoo\u201d along with Justin Davis.  Voodoo was finally released on February 22, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rockdocumented.com/2019/02/08/album-review-lullwater-voodoo/|title=LULLWATER RELEASE VOODOO|date=February 8, 2019}}</ref>  The song Dark Divided off of \"Voodoo\" was listed in The Top 100 Hard Rock Songs of 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://hardrockdaddy.com/2020/01/05/top-100-hard-rock-songs-of-2019/|title=Top 100 Hard Rock Songs of 2019|last=AW|date=January 5, 2020}}</ref> I'm Music Magazine included Lullwater's \u201cVoodoo\u201d among their top 28 Albums of 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://im-musicmagazine.com/f/28-best-albums-of-2019?fbclid=IwAR0TleZYhLJs0-uzDqdegY1BPhIJN4IYBU3vfKMCkZpVOdz4ituVCDiQVuU|title=Top 28 Best Albums from 2019|website=www.im-musicmagazine.com/}}</ref> Dark Divided from \u201cVoodoo\u201d hit number 4 on the Foundations Secondary Market Rock Chart and made it to the most added at [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] Mainstream Rock indicator on October 5, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/rock-songs/2019-10-05 |title=Lullwater's Dark Divided reaches number 4 on Billboards Mainstream Rock Indicator|website=www.billboard.com/|date=October 1, 2019}}</ref> Tours to support \u201cVoodoo\u201d followed while opening for Another Lost Year, [[Gin Blossoms]], [[Collective Soul]], [[Candlebox]], Never Say Die, [[Daughtry (band)|Daughtry]], Kirra, Blacktop Mojo,  [[Powerman 5000]], [[Sevendust]] and [[Tremonti (band)|Tremonti]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blabbermouth.net/news/sevendust-announces-early-2019-u-s-tour-with-tremonti/|title=SEVENDUST Announces Early 2019 U.S. Tour With TREMONTI; BLABBERMOUTH.NET Presale Available|date=November 12, 2018|website=BLABBERMOUTH.NET}}</ref>  Sapphire Bullets ranked Lullwater's Voodoo album as one of the top 50 albums in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sapphirebulletsofpurelove.blogspot.com/?m=1/|title=Lullwater \u2013 Sapphire Bullet's Top Albums of 2019|first=Luke|last=Dunmore|date=December 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n*\u201cLullwater\u201d  (2013)  Released on September 17, 2013\n*\u201cRevival\u201d   (2015)    Released October 23, 2015\n*\u201cVoodoo\u201d   (2019)   Released February 22, 2019\n[[File:Cover of Lullwater, released in 2013.jpg|thumb|Cover of Lullwater, released in 2013]]\n[[File:Revival Cover, released in 2015.jpg|thumb|Revival Cover, released in 2015]]\n[[File:Voodoo Cover, released in 2019.jpg|thumb|Voodoo Cover, released in 2019]]\n\n==Band members==\n'''Current Members'''<br> \n                                                                                                                                                    \n*John Strickland:  Lead vocals and rhythm guitar\n*Joseph Wilson: drums and vocals\n*Roy Beatty: bass and vocals\n*Daniel Binnie:  lead guitar\n\n===Past members===\n*Phil Bush\n*Nick Thomas\n*Brett Strickland\n\n===Instruments===\n*John Strickland:  [[Gibson Les Paul]]\n*Joseph Wilson:  [[Pearl Drums]] / [[Avedis Zildjian Company|Zildjian Cymballs]]\n*Roy Beatty:  [[Dingwall Designer Guitars|Dingwall Guitars]]\n*Daniel Binnie:   [[Gibson Les Paul]]\n\n===Timeline===\n\n{{#tag:timeline\n|ImageSize = width:600 height:auto barincrement:25\nPlotArea   = left:120 bottom:100 top:10 right:10\nAlignbars  = justify\nDateFormat = dd/mm/yyyy\nPeriod     = from:01/01/2007 till:{{#time:d/m/Y}}\nTimeAxis   = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\nLegend     = orientation:vertical position:bottom columns:1\nScaleMajor = increment:2 start:2007\nScaleMinor = increment:1 start:2007\n\nColors = \n id:vocals   value:red       legend:Lead_vocals\n id:guitar   value:green     legend:Guitar\n id:keys     value:purple    legend:Keyboards\n id:bass     value:blue      legend:Bass_guitar\n id:drums    value:orange    legend:Drums\n id:backing  value:pink      legend:Backing_vocals\n id:perc     value:claret    legend:Percussion\n id:album    value:black     legend:Studio_album\n id:bs value:gray(0.1)\n\nLineData =\n layer:back\n color:album\n at:29/12/2013\n at:11/10/2015\n at:22/02/2019\n\nBarData =\n\n bar:JS text:\"John Strickland\"\n bar:BS text:\"Brett Strickland\"\n bar:PB text:\"Phil Bush\"\n bar:NT text:\"Nick Thomas\"\n bar:RB text:\"Roy Beatty\"\n bar:JW text:\"Joseph Wilson\"\n bar:DB text:\"Daniel Binnie\"\n\nPlotData =\n\n bar:JS from:start till:end color:vocals width:13\n bar:JS from:start till:end color:guitar width:3\n\n bar:BS from:start till:22/07/2016 color:guitar width:13\n\n bar:PB from:start till:01/01/2009 color:bass width:13\n\n bar:NT from:start till:01/01/2011 color:drums width:13\n\n bar:RB from:01/01/2009 till:end color:bass width:13\n bar:RB from:01/01/2009 till:end color:backing width:3\n\n bar:JW from:01/01/2011 till:end color:perc width:13\n bar:JW from:01/01/2011 till:end color:drums width:8\n bar:JW from:01/01/2011 till:end color:backing width:3\n\n bar:DB from:22/07/2016 till:end color:guitar width:13\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n\n[[Category:Grunge musical groups]]\n[[Category:American post-grunge musical groups]]\n", "name_user": "Lullwaterfan", "label": "safe", "comment": "working on category", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lullwater_(band)"}
{"title_page": "Kamal Ahmed (journalist)", "text_new": "{{short description|British journalist|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Kamal Ahmed\n| image              = Kamal Ahmed at the 2019 Chiswick Book Festival.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Ahmed at the 2019 Chiswick Book Festival\n| birth_name         = Kamal Ahmed\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1967|11|15|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Ealing]], [[London]], England\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| resting_place      = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence          = \n| nationality        = British\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Elizabeth Day|2011}}\n| awards             = [[CFA Institute|CFA]] Society UK's ethical and professional standards award 2013<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://secure.cfauk.org/assets/3583/Annual_report_30_June_2013_printversion.pdf|title=Annual report|date= 2013-06-30|publisher=CFA UK|format=pdf}}</ref>\n| other_names        = \n| known_for          = \n| title              = Economics Editor of [[BBC News]] {{small|(2016&ndash;2018)}}<br />Business Editor of [[BBC News]] {{small|(2014&ndash;2016)}}<br />Editorial Director of [[BBC News]] {{small|(2018&ndash;present)}}\n| education          = [[Drayton Manor High School]]\n| alma_mater         = [[University of Leeds]]<br>[[City University Department of Journalism]]\n| employer           = [[BBC]]\n| occupation         = [[Journalist]], [[editor]], [[Public administration|administrator]]\n}}\n'''Kamal Ahmed''' (born 15 November 1967 in [[Ealing]], [[London]]) is a [[British people|British]] [[journalist]], currently serving as Editorial Director of [[BBC News]].<ref name=promoted/> He was Economics Editor at the BBC until November 2018, and Business Editor from March 2014, until [[Simon Jack]] was appointed as his successor in February 2016.<ref name=BBC25463326>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-25463326|title=BBC appoints Telegraph's Kamal Ahmed as business editor|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=20 December 2013|accessdate=21 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nAhmed was formerly the political editor of ''[[The Observer]]'', business editor of ''[[The Sunday Telegraph]]'' and Director of Communications at the [[Equality and Human Rights Commission]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nAhmed is the son of an English mother from Rotherham and a Sudanese father who was a research scientist in [[ophthalmology]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ahmed|first1=Kamal|title=After Obama, I can be proud of what I really am: black and white|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/nov/09/mixed-race-barackobama-lewishamilton-human-rights|work=The Observer|date=9 November 2008}}</ref> \nHe grew up in Ealing. From 1980 to 1986, Ahmed was educated at [[Drayton Manor High School]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://moodle.draytonmanorhighschool.co.uk/mod/forum/discuss.php?d=241|title=Alumni News - Kamal Ahmed|publisher=Drayton Manor High School, Hanwell|date=11 June 2014|accessdate=11 June 2014}}</ref> a state comprehensive school in [[Hanwell]] in the [[London Borough of Ealing]] in West London, followed by the [[University of Leeds]], from which he graduated in 1990 with a degree in political studies.<ref name=Leeds>{{cite web|url=http://www.polis.leeds.ac.uk/about/after-polis/polis-alumni.php|title=Who's been here? &#124; Politics and International Studies (POLIS)|publisher=University of Leeds|accessdate=3 January 2014}}</ref> He then trained in journalism at the [[City University Department of Journalism]].\n\n==Career==\nAhmed worked on local newspapers in Scotland before joining ''[[Scotland on Sunday]]'' in 1993.<ref name=BBCb01696pp>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01696pp|title=BBC Radio 5 live - On the Money|publisher=BBC|date=23 October 2011|accessdate=3 January 2014}}</ref> He later moved to ''[[The Guardian]]'' and became executive news editor and political editor at ''[[The Observer]]'' newspaper.<ref name=BBC25463326/> Ahmed was later criticised by fellow journalist [[Nick Davies]] for maintaining an inappropriately close relationship with [[Downing Street]] while serving as political editor, and for publishing numerous articles that \"contained significant falsehood or distortion\".<ref>Davies, Nick, ''Flat Earth News'', 340-385.</ref> Ahmed described Davies' claims as untrue and \"hearsay\".<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/kamal-ahmed-nick-is-a-coward-ahmed-bites-back-780670.html|title=Kamal Ahmed: 'Nick is a coward'. Ahmed bites back|first=Michael|last=Savage|publisher=[[The Independent]]|date=11 February 2008|accessdate=7 July 2016}}</ref> After leaving the newspaper, he then became group Director of Communications at the [[Equality and Human Rights Commission]],<ref name=BBC25463326/> recruited by its then chairman [[Trevor Phillips]].<ref name=GuardQuit/>\n\nIn 2009, Ahmed was appointed business editor for ''[[The Sunday Telegraph]]'',<ref name=GuardQuit>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2009/jul/26/trevor-phillips-equality-watchdog|title=Trevor Phillips 'shocked' as ally quits watchdog|first=Helen|last=Pidd|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|date=26 July 2009|accessdate=21 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/wire/5372|title=Former Observer exec Kamal Ahmed joins Sunday Telegraph|first=Oliver|last=Luft|publisher=[[Press Gazette]]|date=27 July 2009|accessdate=21 December 2013}}</ref> undertaking a course at the [[London Business School]] before replacing Mark Kleinman, who left for [[Sky News]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cityam.com/article/new-sunday-telegraph-business-editor-steep-learning-curve|title=New Sunday Telegraph Business Editor on Steep Learning Curve|first=Victoria|last=Bates|publisher=City AM|date=21 August 2009|accessdate=21 December 2013}}</ref> In 2013 he became executive business editor, with a role across the ''Sunday'' and ''Daily Telegraph'' print editions.<ref name=BBC25463326/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/comment/kamal-ahmed/|title=Column - Kamal Ahmed|publisher=[[Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=21 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 December 2013, it was announced that Ahmed would replace [[Robert Peston]] as the business editor of BBC News,<ref name=BBC25463326/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2013/dec/20/bbc-business-editor-kamal-ahmed-telegraph|title=BBC appoints Sunday Telegraph's Kamal Ahmed as business editor|first=John|last=Plunkett|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|date=20 December 2013|accessdate=21 December 2013}}</ref> and on 24 March 2014 he assumed the post.\n\nOn 3 December 2015, after Peston's departure to ITV, it was announced that Ahmed would replace him as the BBC economics editor, with his successor as business editor of BBC News would be announced early in 2016.<ref name=promoted>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2015/kamal-ahmed-economics-editor|title=BBC - Kamal Ahmed appointed new BBC Economics Editor - Media Centre|website=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 July 2018, Ahmed was announced as BBC News' Editorial Director,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2018/kamal-ahmed-gavin-allen|title=BBC - BBC announces Kamal Ahmed as Editorial Director and Gavin Allen as Head of News Output - Media Centre|website=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> with [[Faisal Islam]] replacing him in his previous role.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prolificnorth.co.uk/news/broadcasting/2018/11/sky-news-political-editor-defects-bbc|title=Sky News Political Editor defects to BBC|date=2018-11-06|website=Prolific North|language=en|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAhmed married the journalist and novelist [[Elizabeth Day]] in December 2011.<ref>[http://www.malvernstjames.co.uk/documents/website%20downloads%2012/oganewsletterspr2013.pdf \"MGC News\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131212013955/http://www.malvernstjames.co.uk/documents/website%20downloads%2012/oganewsletterspr2013.pdf |date=12 December 2013 }}, Malvern St James, ''OGA News'', Spring 2013, p.17</ref> The couple separated in February 2015 and are now divorced.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/life/weekend/cambridge-graduate-a-successful-career-as-an-awardwinning-author-and-journalist-invitations-to-alist-parties-why-life-is-good-for-elizabeth-day-36016461.html|title=Cambridge graduate, a successful career as an award-winning author and journalist, invitations to A-list parties... why life is good for Elizabeth Day|work=BelfastTelegraph.co.uk|access-date=2019-11-22|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=7058177|name=Kamal Ahmed}}\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/correspondents/kamalahmed/ BBC News - Kamal Ahmed's BBC 'Business Blog']\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/search/news/?q=Kamal+Ahmed BBC News - Kamal Ahmed articles] \n*[https://mobile.twitter.com/bbckamal Twitter - Kamal Ahmed, BBC Business Editor]\n*[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/comment/kamal-ahmed/ Column @ ''Daily Telegraph]''\n*[http://journalisted.com/kamal-ahmed#tab-work Journalisted - Kamal Ahmed]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{Succession box\n| before = [[Robert Peston]]\n| title = Business Editor: [[BBC News]]\n| years = 2014\u20132016\n| after = [[Simon Jack]]\n}}\n{{Succession box\n| before = [[Robert Peston]]\n| title = Economics Editor: [[BBC News]]\n| years = 2016\u20132018\n| after = [[Faisal Islam]]\n}}\n{{Succession box\n| before = Position established\n| title = Editorial Director: [[BBC News]]\n| years = 2018\u2013present\n| after = Incumbent\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ahmed, Kamal}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Drayton Manor High School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of City, University of London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Leeds]]\n[[Category:BBC newsreaders and journalists]]\n[[Category:Black British television personalities]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:English people of Sudanese descent]]\n[[Category:People from Ealing]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British journalist|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Kamal Ahmed\n| image              = Kamal Ahmed at the 2019 Chiswick Book Festival.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Ahmed at the 2019 Chiswick Book Festival\n| birth_name         = Kamal Ahmed\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1967|11|15|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Ealing]], [[London]], England\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| resting_place      = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence          = \n| nationality        = British\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Elizabeth Day|2011}}\n| awards             = [[CFA Institute|CFA]] Society UK's ethical and professional standards award 2013<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://secure.cfauk.org/assets/3583/Annual_report_30_June_2013_printversion.pdf|title=Annual report|date= 2013-06-30|publisher=CFA UK|format=pdf}}</ref>\n| other_names        = \n| known_for          = \n| title              = Economics Editor of [[BBC News]] {{small|(2016&ndash;2018)}}<br />Business Editor of [[BBC News]] {{small|(2014&ndash;2016)}}<br />Editorial Director of [[BBC News]] {{small|(2018&ndash;present)}}\n| education          = [[Drayton Manor High School]]\n| alma_mater         = [[University of Leeds]]<br>[[City University Department of Journalism]]\n| employer           = [[BBC]]\n| occupation         = [[Journalist]], [[editor]], [[Public administration|administrator]]\n}}\n'''Kamal Ahmed''' (born 15 November 1967 in [[Ealing]], [[London]]) is a [[British people|British]] [[journalist]], currently serving as Editorial Director of [[BBC News]].<ref name=promoted/> He was Economics Editor at the BBC until November 2018, and Business Editor from March 2014, until [[Simon Jack]] was appointed as his successor in February 2016.<ref name=BBC25463326>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-25463326|title=BBC appoints Telegraph's Kamal Ahmed as business editor|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=20 December 2013|accessdate=21 December 2013}}</ref> \n\nAhmed was formerly the political editor of ''[[The Observer]]'', business editor of ''[[The Sunday Telegraph]]'' and Director of Communications at the [[Equality and Human Rights Commission]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nAhmed is the son of an English mother from Rotherham and a Sudanese father who was a research scientist in [[ophthalmology]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ahmed|first1=Kamal|title=After Obama, I can be proud of what I really am: black and white|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/nov/09/mixed-race-barackobama-lewishamilton-human-rights|work=The Observer|date=9 November 2008}}</ref> \nHe grew up in Ealing. From 1980 to 1986, Ahmed was educated at [[Drayton Manor High School]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://moodle.draytonmanorhighschool.co.uk/mod/forum/discuss.php?d=241|title=Alumni News - Kamal Ahmed|publisher=Drayton Manor High School, Hanwell|date=11 June 2014|accessdate=11 June 2014}}</ref> a state comprehensive school in [[Hanwell]] in the [[London Borough of Ealing]] in West London, followed by the [[University of Leeds]], from which he graduated in 1990 with a degree in political studies.<ref name=Leeds>{{cite web|url=http://www.polis.leeds.ac.uk/about/after-polis/polis-alumni.php|title=Who's been here? &#124; Politics and International Studies (POLIS)|publisher=University of Leeds|accessdate=3 January 2014}}</ref> He then trained in journalism at the [[City University Department of Journalism]].\n\n==Career==\nAhmed worked on local newspapers in Scotland before joining ''[[Scotland on Sunday]]'' in 1993.<ref name=BBCb01696pp>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01696pp|title=BBC Radio 5 live - On the Money|publisher=BBC|date=23 October 2011|accessdate=3 January 2014}}</ref> He later moved to ''[[The Guardian]]'' and became executive news editor and political editor at ''[[The Observer]]'' newspaper.<ref name=BBC25463326/> Ahmed was later criticised by fellow journalist [[Nick Davies]] for maintaining an inappropriately close relationship with [[Downing Street]] while serving as political editor, and for publishing numerous articles that \"contained significant falsehood or distortion\".<ref>Davies, Nick, ''Flat Earth News'', 340-385.</ref> Ahmed described Davies' claims as untrue and \"hearsay\".<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/kamal-ahmed-nick-is-a-coward-ahmed-bites-back-780670.html|title=Kamal Ahmed: 'Nick is a coward'. Ahmed bites back|first=Michael|last=Savage|publisher=[[The Independent]]|date=11 February 2008|accessdate=7 July 2016}}</ref> After leaving the newspaper, he then became group Director of Communications at the [[Equality and Human Rights Commission]],<ref name=BBC25463326/> recruited by its then chairman [[Trevor Phillips]].<ref name=GuardQuit/>\n\nIn 2009, Ahmed was appointed business editor for ''[[The Sunday Telegraph]]'',<ref name=GuardQuit>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2009/jul/26/trevor-phillips-equality-watchdog|title=Trevor Phillips 'shocked' as ally quits watchdog|first=Helen|last=Pidd|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|date=26 July 2009|accessdate=21 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/wire/5372|title=Former Observer exec Kamal Ahmed joins Sunday Telegraph|first=Oliver|last=Luft|publisher=[[Press Gazette]]|date=27 July 2009|accessdate=21 December 2013}}</ref> undertaking a course at the [[London Business School]] before replacing Mark Kleinman, who left for [[Sky News]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cityam.com/article/new-sunday-telegraph-business-editor-steep-learning-curve|title=New Sunday Telegraph Business Editor on Steep Learning Curve|first=Victoria|last=Bates|publisher=City AM|date=21 August 2009|accessdate=21 December 2013}}</ref> In 2013 he became executive business editor, with a role across the ''Sunday'' and ''Daily Telegraph'' print editions.<ref name=BBC25463326/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/comment/kamal-ahmed/|title=Column - Kamal Ahmed|publisher=[[Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=21 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 December 2013, it was announced that Ahmed would replace [[Robert Peston]] as the business editor of BBC News,<ref name=BBC25463326/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2013/dec/20/bbc-business-editor-kamal-ahmed-telegraph|title=BBC appoints Sunday Telegraph's Kamal Ahmed as business editor|first=John|last=Plunkett|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|date=20 December 2013|accessdate=21 December 2013}}</ref> and on 24 March 2014 he assumed the post.\n\nOn 3 December 2015, after Peston's departure to ITV, it was announced that Ahmed would replace him as the BBC economics editor, with his successor as business editor of BBC News would be announced early in 2016.<ref name=promoted>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2015/kamal-ahmed-economics-editor|title=BBC - Kamal Ahmed appointed new BBC Economics Editor - Media Centre|website=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 July 2018, Ahmed was announced as BBC News' Editorial Director,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2018/kamal-ahmed-gavin-allen|title=BBC - BBC announces Kamal Ahmed as Editorial Director and Gavin Allen as Head of News Output - Media Centre|website=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> with [[Faisal Islam]] replacing him in his previous role.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prolificnorth.co.uk/news/broadcasting/2018/11/sky-news-political-editor-defects-bbc|title=Sky News Political Editor defects to BBC|date=2018-11-06|website=Prolific North|language=en|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAhmed married the journalist and novelist [[Elizabeth Day]] in December 2011.<ref>[http://www.malvernstjames.co.uk/documents/website%20downloads%2012/oganewsletterspr2013.pdf \"MGC News\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131212013955/http://www.malvernstjames.co.uk/documents/website%20downloads%2012/oganewsletterspr2013.pdf |date=12 December 2013 }}, Malvern St James, ''OGA News'', Spring 2013, p.17</ref> The couple separated in February 2015 and are now divorced.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/life/weekend/cambridge-graduate-a-successful-career-as-an-awardwinning-author-and-journalist-invitations-to-alist-parties-why-life-is-good-for-elizabeth-day-36016461.html|title=Cambridge graduate, a successful career as an award-winning author and journalist, invitations to A-list parties... why life is good for Elizabeth Day|work=BelfastTelegraph.co.uk|access-date=2019-11-22|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=7058177|name=Kamal Ahmed}}\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/correspondents/kamalahmed/ BBC News - Kamal Ahmed's BBC 'Business Blog']\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/search/news/?q=Kamal+Ahmed BBC News - Kamal Ahmed articles] \n*[https://mobile.twitter.com/bbckamal Twitter - Kamal Ahmed, BBC Business Editor]\n*[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/comment/kamal-ahmed/ Column @ ''Daily Telegraph]''\n*[http://journalisted.com/kamal-ahmed#tab-work Journalisted - Kamal Ahmed]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{Succession box\n| before = [[Robert Peston]]\n| title = Business Editor: [[BBC News]]\n| years = 2014\u20132016\n| after = [[Simon Jack]]\n}}\n{{Succession box\n| before = [[Robert Peston]]\n| title = Economics Editor: [[BBC News]]\n| years = 2016\u20132018\n| after = [[Faisal Islam]]\n}}\n{{Succession box\n| before = Position established\n| title = Editorial Director: [[BBC News]]\n| years = 2018\u2013present\n| after = Incumbent\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ahmed, Kamal}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Drayton Manor High School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of City, University of London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Leeds]]\n[[Category:BBC newsreaders and journalists]]\n[[Category:Black British television personalities]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:English people of Sudanese descent]]\n[[Category:People from Ealing]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kamal_Ahmed_(journalist)"}
{"title_page": "Banswara", "text_new": "{{About|the municipality in Rajasthan, India|its namesake district|Banswara district}}\n{{advert|date=March 2012}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Banswara\n| settlement_type         = City\n| image_skyline           = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| pushpin_map             = India Rajasthan\n| pushpin_label_position  = right\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in Rajasthan, India\n| coordinates             = {{coord|23.55|N|74.45|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Rajasthan]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Banswara district|Banswara]]\n| established_title       = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| named_for               = \n| government_type         = nagar parishad\n| governing_body          = congress\n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = 302\n| population_total        = 100,128\n| population_as_of        = 2011\n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| demographics_type1      = Languages\n|demographics1_title2=Spoken\n|demographics1_info2=[[Wagdi language|Wagdi]]\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code             = 327001\n| area_code_type          = Telephone code\n| area_code               = 02962\n| registration_plate      = RJ-03\n| blank1_name_sec1        = [[Human sex ratio|Sex ratio]]\n| blank1_info_sec1        = 954 females per 1000 males\n| website                 = {{URL|http://banswara.rajasthan.gov.in/}}\n| iso_code                = [[ISO 3166-2:IN|RJ-IN]]\n| footnotes               =\n \n}}\n\n'''Banswara''' is a city in [[Banswara District]] in south [[Rajasthan]] in India. The state of [[Banswara State|Banswara]] was founded by Bansiya bhil. It is named for the \"bans\" or [[bamboo]] forests in the area..\n\nIt is also known as 'City of Hundred Islands' or 'CherraPoonji of Rajasthan', due to highest rain in [[Rajasthan]] and presence of numerous islands on the [[Mahi River]] named \"Chachakota\" where the islands located, which flows through Banswara. The city is governed by City Council (Nagar Parishad) which comes under Banswara Urban Agglomeration. The city has population of 100,128, its urban / metropolitan population is 101,177 of which 51,941 are males and 49,236 are females.<ref>{{cite web|title=Banswara District population|url=Parathapur disturbances in stock of big tea business, penalty recovery with tax of 11 lakhs|accessdate=27 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nBanswara is located at {{Coord|23.55|N|74.45|E|}}.<ref>[http://www.fallingrain.com/world/IN/24/Banswara.html Falling Rain Genomics, Inc \u2013 Banswara]</ref> It has an average elevation of 302&nbsp;metres (990&nbsp;ft).\n\n[[Banswara District]] is in southern Rajasthan with an area of {{convert|5999|km2|mi2}} located between 23.11\u00b0 N to 23.56\u00b0 N latitudes and 73.58\u00b0 E to 74.49\u00b0 E. longitudes. It is bounded on the north-east by Dhariawad, Pipalkoot & Arnod tehsils of Pratapgarh district of Rajasthan; on the east by Ratlam district of Madhya Pradesh; on the west by Sagwara and on north-west by Aspur tehsils of Dungarpur district of Rajasthan; on the south-east by Jhabua district of Madhya Pradesh and on south & south-west the Dohad district of Gujarat.\nThe region represents a rugged terrain undulated by short ridges west of Banswara. The eastern part of it is occupied by flat-topped hills of the Deccan trap. It has the southern end of the Aravali mountains. The drainage system belongs to the [[Mahi River|Mahi]] river which originates from Amjera hills near Dhar in Madhya Preadesh. Its main tributaries are Anas, Chanp, Erav, Hiran and Kagdi. The [[Mahi Bajaj Sagar Dam]] has been constructed on the Mahi, about {{convert|16|km|mi}} away from Banswara town. The Right and Left Main Canals and their distributaries irrigate {{convert|60149|ha|km2}} of land. Normal annual rainfall is about {{convert|82.59|cm|in}}.\n\nThe main crops are maize, wheat, rice, cotton soya bean and gram. Graphite, soapstone, dolomite, rock phosphate, limestone and a variety of marbles are mined in the region, with some deposits of gold found around Jagpura. About 20% of the area is designated as forested land, but most of the forest land is devoid of trees in the non-monsoon months.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://banswara.nic.in/e_geo.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-04-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721163344/http://www.banswara.nic.in/e_geo.htm |archivedate=2011-07-21 }}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n{{Main|Banswara State}}\nBanswara (literally \"the bamboo country\") was a Rajput feudatory state in [[Rajputana]] during [[British India]]. It borders [[Gujarat]] and is bounded on the north by the native states of [[Dungarpur]] and [[Udaipur]] or [[Mewar]]; on the northeast and east by [[Pratapgarh district, Rajasthan|Partapgarh]]; on the south by the dominions of [[Indore State|Holkar]] and the state of [[Jhabua State|Jabua]]; and on the west by the state of [[Rewa Kantha]].\n\nBanswara state was about {{convert|45|mi|km}} in length from north to south and {{convert|33|mi|km}} in breadth from east to west and had an area of {{convert|1606|mi2|km2}}.<ref>{{EB1911|inline=1|wstitle=Banswara|volume=3|page=355}}</ref> The population in 1941 was 258,760.<ref>{{cite web|title=Princely History of Banswara|url=http://princelystatesofindia.com/Princely/banswara.html|accessdate=3 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nBanswara district forms eastern part of the region known as [[Vagad]] or Vagwar. The district was formerly a state ruled by the Maharavals. It is said that a [[Bhil people|Bhil]] ruler Bansia or Wasna, ruled over it and Banswara was named after his name. Bansia was defeated and killed by Jagmal Singh who became the first Maharaval of the princely state. It is named so because of the [[bamboo]] which were found in abundance in the forests.\n\nBanswara massacre is also known as Rajasthan's \u2018[[Jallianwala Bagh massacre|Jallianwala Bagh]]\u2019, a little known event of the British Raj era.{{cn}}\n\nOn 17 November 1913, [[Banswara district]] of South Rajasthan was witness to a little-known massacre of around 1500 tribals by the British, echoing the [[Jallianwala Bagh massacre]] in which 329 people were killed in firing. British forces opened fire on tribals who had gathered on the Mangarh hillock situated in the [[Aravalli Range|Aravali]] mountains on the Rajasthan-Gujarat border. The tribals were led by their leader Govind Guru who inspired them to throw off the yoke of British rule.\n\nGovind Guru, influenced by social reformers like [[Dayananda Saraswati|Dayanand Saraswat]]<nowiki/>i, launched the 'Bhagat movement among the Bhils asking them to adhere to vegetarianism, and abstain from all types of intoxicants. The movement slowly took on a political hue and turned into a movement against the oppressive policies of the [[United Kingdom|British]].\n\nThe Bhils began opposing taxes imposed by the [[United Kingdom|British]] and forced labour imposed by the princely states of Banswara, [[Santrampur]], [[Dungarpur]] and [[Kushalgarh]]. Worried by the tribal revolt, the Britishers and princely states decided to crush the uprising. From October 1913, [[Govindguru|''Govind guru'']] asked his followers to gather at Mangarh hill from where they would conduct their operations.\n\nThe British asked them to vacate Mangarh hill by 15 November, but they refused. On 17 November, the tribals were gathering for a meeting when the British forces under Maj S Bailey and Capt E Stiley opened fire from cannons and guns on the crowd. Though there are no official estimates, locals say about 2500 people were killed in cold blood.\n\nGovind guru was captured and exiled from the area. He was imprisoned in [[Hyderabad]] jail and released in 1919 on grounds of good behavior. But as he was exiled from his homeland, he settled in [[Limdi]] in [[Gujarat]] where he died in 1931. The site of the massacre is today known as [[Mangarh Dham]] and the locals are demanding that a national memorial be built there in memory of the martyrs.\n\n== Tourism ==\n\n=== Andheswar Parshwanathji ===\n[[File:Andeshwar_Jain_Temple.JPG|thumb|Main idol at [[Andeshwar Parshwanath]] ]]\n[[Andeshwar Parshwanath]]ji is situated on a hillock in Kushalgarh tehsil of Banswara district. This is a famous Jain temple housing rare Shilalekhs of the 10th century. We could find two Digamabara Jain Parshwanatha temples at this place. The main temple was built by Digamabar Jain Panchayat of Kushalgarh.\n\n===Anekant Bahubali Temple Lohariya===\nAnekant Bahubali Temple is situated in Banswara-Udaipur Road in Lohariya Tehsil Ghari of Banswara District. This Jain temple is Famous for the 27-foot Standing Statue of Lord Bahubali which is made of White Sangmarar (marble). This Jain temple was made by the Inspiration of Digamber Acharya Shri 108 Bharat Sagarji maharaj here we can find many other temples of Jain Lords Like Panch Parmeshti Jinalay (tample), Manvadi Sapt charan Rishi's Tample, Adinatha Jinalaya etc. Has situated in The Campus of temple.\n\n=== Abdullah Pir ===\nAbdullah Pir is a Dargah of Sayedi Abdul Rasul Saheed, a Muslim saint and mostly visited by the Bohra Muslim. It's an important holy place for the Bohras. Abdullah Pir is located in the southern part of the city. On 10th Rabi' al-awwal, every year \"Urs\" is held at the Dargah. The people of the Bohara community take part in it in large numbers. This is a Muslim shrine of Dawoodi Bohras saint and is mostly visited by Dawoodi Bohra Muslims who visit this place during URS.\n\n=== Anand Sagar Lake ===\nThis artificial lake has been constructed by Lanchi Bai, the Rani of Maharval Jagami. It is also known as Bai Talab. Anand Sagar Lake is located on the eastern part of Banswara. It is enclosed by the holy trees named 'Kalpa Vriksha', famous for fulfilling the desire of the visitors. Nearby lies the chattris or cenotaphs of the rulers of the state.\n\n[[File: ARTHUNA TEMPLE.jpg|thumb]]\n\n=== Arthuna ===\nArthuna, as well as its surrounding areas, have clusters of ruined Hindu and Jain temples belonging to the 11th, 12th and the 15th centuries. Among the dilapidated ruins is a carved conjugated statue of Shiva, Parvati and Ganesh. Lankiya village around Arthuna has Shaivite temples called Nilkanth Mahadev Temples. The temple is an old stone temple having intricate carvings and sculpted figures of women embedded in the outer walls. The bull Nandi (Lord Shiva's faithful vehicle) stands guard at the entrance in the temple porch.<ref>http://techandtricki.com/banswara-tourism-tourist-places-in-banswara-rajasthan/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180109235540/http://techandtricki.com/banswara-tourism-tourist-places-in-banswara-rajasthan/ |date=9 January 2018 }} BANSWARA TOURISM</ref>\n\n=== Dailab Lake ===\nMorning [[aarti]] of Lord Hanuman followed by sunrise behind the hills with beautiful scenery through Dialab Lake can be observed at this Place. This place is situated on [[Pratapgarh district, Rajasthan|Pratapgarh]] Road, civil lines.  A well-made 'Harihar Maruti Dham' [[temple]] is situated near this lake. A popular place for devotees of [[Hanuman|Lord Hanuman]] during the day of [[Hanuman Jayanti]]. \n\nIn recent years water hyacinth has invaded whole lake which disappoints its visitors. Many steps haven been taken to remove this weed but all resulted failures.\n\n=== Madareshwar Temple ===\nBanswara has a number of ancient Hindu and Jain temples, and in the past was known as Lodi Kashi or the city of temples. This famous temple of Lord Shiva is situated inside the natural cave of a high hill on the eastern part of the city. It presents a sensational natural view. The cave temple provides an Amarnath Yatra like feeling to the pilgrims, due to its typical location.\n\n=== Mahi Dam ===\nMahi Dam is one of the major attractions of Banswara. It is situated 16 kilometres from Banswara town in Banswara district Rajasthan, India. The dam was constructed between 1972 and 1983 under the Mahi Bajaj Sagar Project, for the purposes of hydroelectric power generation and water supply.various dams and canals have been constructed over an enticingly enchanting scenic surrounding. Near the dam, you could locate the enticing garden with fountain. It is the second largest dam in Rajasthan.\n\n=== Mangarh Dham ===\nThis is an important fair of the tribals and is held on Margshirsha Purnima. At this fair the tribals of [[Rajasthan]], [[Madhya Pradesh]] &\n[[Gujarat]] participate and they pay tribute to Guru [[Govindgiri]], founder of the Samp sabha.\n\n=== Paraheada ===\nParaheada is located in the Garhi Tehsil. It is famous temple of Lord Shiva. It was constructed by the Mandlik. Paraheada is 22&nbsp;km from Banswara.\nShri Raj Mandir or more popularly known as the City Palace was built in the 16th century and situated on a hillock overlooking the town. Covering a huge area it follows typical style of old Rajput architecture. Though lack of funds has made many royal palaces of Rajasthan exchange hands with the government after Independence, this palace is still owned by the Royal family\n\n=== Bhim kund ===\nIt is a place surrounded by hills. People call it \"Phati Khan\" because it is a deep cave under a hill. There is a pool of very cold water which is found throughout the year. It is said that Lord Ram, during his exile came and stayed here for some time.\n\n=== Talwada ===\nTalwara is another place to visit near Banswara. Its historical significance due to its primeval temples and the devastated of some old monuments. Talwara is the temples of Sun, Lord Amaliya Ganesh, Laxmi Narayan Temple, and Jain Temple of Sambhavnath make Talwara a religiously important site. The idols in these temples are carved in local black stone.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\n=== Kupda ===\n\nkupda is another place to visit near Banswara. It is famous temple of VEJVA MATA. Temple is situated in Banswara-Dungarpur Road near mayur mill.\n\n=== Tripura Sundari ===\n[[File:Shri tripura sundari temple.JPG|thumb|Shri Tripura Sundari Temple]]\nTripura Sundari is the temple, devoted to Goddess Tripura Sundari or Turita Mata. This temple has a gorgeous idol of black stone having 18 hands and more important each hand carrying a different emblem. The Goddess is seen riding a tiger. It is believed that its one of the Shakti Peeths of Hindus having divine powers. It is believed that this temple was built before Samrat Kanishka, who rule here. The exact date of its construction is not yet known. It is said to be one of the \"Shakti Peeths\" of the Hindus having charismatic divine power. But it is believed that the temple was constructed approximately before the reign of the Kushana emperor Kanishka who ruled here in the first century AD.\n\n=== Sai Tample ===\nSai tample is most viewed place in banswara, This is the temple of god Sai baba. The Om Sri Shirdi Sai Baba temple established in 2004. This temple is not only settled you with peace of mind but also providing the dish of love who is visiting here on Thursday by the trust.<ref>patrika.com/banswara-news/banswara-sai-baba-temple-every-thrusday-bhandara-2633115/</ref> This temple has a big size idol of white stone of [[Sai Baba of Shirdi|''Sai baba'']] and also one god ganesh, This temple have unique ''[[rangoli]]'' of stone inside temple, and a big jhumar light on roof, there's a big open place in front of temple\n\nOne side of this temple one big pyramid hall, and one statue of [[Mahavira|''Mahaveer swami'']] .From this side we watch one [http://hi.krishnakosh.org/%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%83%E0%A4%B7%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%A3/%E0%A4%A4%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%B0%E0%A4%BF%E0%A4%B6%E0%A5%82%E0%A4%B2_%E0%A4%85%E0%A4%B8%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%A4%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%B0 ''Trishul''] , and [[Om|''\u0950'']] sign which made by stones on mountains.\n\nOther side open place which have children's play items like Jhula, slides etc. and also view of water of [http://india-wris.nrsc.gov.in/wrpinfo/index.php?title=Kagdi_Weir_W00133 ''Kagdi pick up weir''] also one statue of [[State Emblem of India]]\n\n== Location ==\n\nThe Banswara district lies in the southernmost part of [[Rajasthan]]. It is surrounded by [[Pratapgarh, Rajasthan|Pratapgarh]] in the north, [[Dungarpur]] in the west, [[Ratlam]] and [[Jhabua]] districts of [[Madhya Pradesh]] in the east and south and [[Dahod district]], [[Gujarat]] to the south.\n\n=== Distance from major cities ===\n\nThe closest major city to Banswara is [[Udaipur]] which is 165&nbsp;km away. [[Indore]] and [[Ahmedabad]] are also close, at 215&nbsp;km and 245&nbsp;km away respectively. The [[town]] is 827&nbsp;km from [[New Delhi]] and 710&nbsp;km from [[Mumbai]].\n\n== Development and technical education ==\n\nSince 2012 Government engineering College has been started and in State Budget of 2013\u201314 declared for Starting of one Medical college in Banswara .{{when|date=October 2012}}\n\nFor opening of one [[Nuclear power|nuclear]] power plant, & Two Super critical thermal power plant & Railway line ([[Ratlam district|Ratlam]] -[[Dungarpur district|Dungarpur]] via [[Banswara district|Banswara]]) various Proceeding of State Govt is going on.{{when|date=October 2012}}\n\n== Demographics ==\n{{bar box\n|title=Religions in Banswara\n|titlebar=#Fcd116\n|left1=Religion\n|right1=Percent\n|float=right\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|[[Hindus]]|orange|64.83}}\n{{bar percent|[[Muslims]]|green|26.32}}\n}}\n{{As of|2001}} India [[census]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.net/results/town.php?stad=A&state5=999|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040616075334/http://www.censusindia.net/results/town.php?stad=A&state5=999|archivedate=2004-06-16|title= Census of India 2001: Data from the 2001 Census, including cities, villages and towns (Provisional)|accessdate=2008-11-01|publisher= Census Commission of India}}</ref> Banswara city had a population of 101,177. Males constitute 51% of the population and females 49%. Banswara city has an average literacy rate of 86.98%, higher than the national average of 59.5%, with 92.76% of the males and 81.01% of females literate.\n\n== Culture ==\n[[File:Kangra pick up weir.jpg|thumb|Kagdi Pick Up Weir]]\nSituated amidst the [[Aravali Range|Aravali]] valley, Banswara represents tribal culture in Rajasthan. With a landscape predominated by bamboo trees ({{lang-hi|\u092c\u093e\u0901\u0938}}) the region came to be known as Banswara. Banswara town was founded by King Jagmal Singh.<ref>{{cite web|title=Banswara District |url=http://banswara.nic.in/e_culture.htm |publisher=NIC |accessdate=3 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120418062809/http://banswara.nic.in/e_culture.htm |archivedate=18 April 2012 }}</ref> The town has eleven and a half Swayambhoo [[Shivalinga]]s; it was also called 'Lodhikashi' or little [[Varanasi|Kashi]].  Yet another name is 'An Area of Hundred Islands'. Situated in southern Rajasthan, the town borders [[Gujarat]] and [[Madhya Pradesh]]. Due to this inter-regional neighborhood, the Vagdi culture has emerged as a mixture of Gujarati, Malwi, Rajasthani and Mewari cultures.  Banswara district is rich in forests, hills and wildlife.  Tribals are the natives of this region.\n\n== Climate and rainfall ==\n\nThe district has a climate which is milder than that in the desert regions in further north and north-west.\n* Maximum temperature is 45 degrees Celsius to 46 degrees Celsius.\n* Minimum temperature is 10 degrees Celsius to 20 degrees Celsius\n* Normal annual rainfall is 922.4&nbsp;mm\n\n== Civic administration ==\n[[Banswara Municipal Board]] has been upgraded to Municipal council (Nagar Parishad).\n\n== Government and politics ==\n\nIn 2018 the MLA of this region is [Arjun Singh Bamaniya].\n\nHaridev Joshi belong to a village name Khandu in Banswara district remained chief minister of Rajasthan 3 times. Under haridev Joshi Banswara seen lots of development most prominent one was construnction of Mahi Bajaj Sagar dam which transformed the economy and living standard of whole district.\n\n== Utility services ==\nThe total transformer capacity in the district is 63.1 MV\u00b7A. Of the 1,431 villages 1,219 villages were electrified up to 31 March 2000.\n\nThe [[Mahi river]] flows on the borders of Peepalkhoot and Ghatol and Banswara Panchayat Samitis. The Mahi project has the capacity to irrigate an area of 800 square kilometres.\n\n== Transport ==\n\n=== Road ===\n\nRoad transport is the only mode of goods and passengers movement from and to the district. The district headquarters has direct road connection with [[Ratlam]], [[Dungarpur]], [[Dahod]] and [[Jaipur]]. Total road length in the district is 1,747&nbsp;km, as of 31 March 2000.\n\n=== Rail ===\n\nThe Railway Ministry has approved railway line to be established to connect the [[Dungarpur]] and [[Ratlam]] station. The total distance between Ratlam to Dungarpur is around 187.6&nbsp;km (116.56&nbsp;mi), Banswara is situated in the centre of these two stations. Recently railway line work in progress and final location for rail track marked by agency.\n\n=== Air ===\n\nThe nearest airport is at [[Udaipur]] {{convert|165|km|mi}}, where there is a helipad and runways for charter planes to Talwada village airstrip around {{convert|13|km|mi}} from Banswara city. There is no airport at Banswara itself, but nearby at Udaipur {{convert|160|km|mi}}, Indore (Madhya Pradesh) {{convert|212|km|mi}} & Ahmedabad (Guj) {{convert|285|km|mi}} are major airports close to Banswara.\n\n== Education ==\n\nSchools and higher educational institutions in Banswara are administered either by the Directorate of Education, the government, or private organizations. In 2008\u201309, there were 1,995 primary and middle schools, 283 secondary and senior secondary schools in the city. The higher education institutions in the city included Two Govt P.G.Colleges and & Eight Private colleges .For Technical education one Govt. POLYTECHNIC & one Govt. ENGINEERING COLLEGE & Two ITIs.\n\nPrivate schools in the city\u2014which employ either English or Hindi as the language of instruction\u2014are affiliated to one of two administering bodies: the [[Rajasthan Board of Secondary Education]] and the [[Central Board for Secondary Education]].\n\nsome school for example:- Kendriya vidyalaya, St. Paul senior secondary school, Ankur senior secondary school,\n\n== Media ==\n\nThe focus on political reportage, including regular television broadcasts of Indian parliament sessions. Many country-wide media agencies, among them the state-owned [[Press Trust of India]] and [[Doordarshan]], are based in the city. Television programming in the city includes two free terrestrial television channels offered by Doordarshan, and several Hindi, English and regional-languages cable channels offered by multi-system operators. Satellite television, in contrast, is yet to gain large-scale subscribership in the city.\n\nPrint journalism remains a popular news medium. During the year 2005\u201306, newspapers\u2014in Hindi languages\u2014were published from the city. Of these, Hindi language newspapers, and included [[Dainik Bhaskar]], [[Rajasthan Patrika]]. Other major English newspapers include ''[[Indian Express]]'', ''[[Business Standard]]'', ''[[The Times of India]]'', ''[[The Hindu]]''.\n\n== Notable people ==\n*[[Haridev Joshi]], former Chief Minister of Rajasthan\n*[[Imam Siddique]], Big Boss Runner Up\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Banswara district}}\n{{Rajasthan}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Banswara district]]\n[[Category:Cities in Malwa]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the municipality in Rajasthan, India|its namesake district|Banswara district}}\n{{advert|date=March 2012}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Banswara\n| settlement_type         = City\n| image_skyline           = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| pushpin_map             = India Rajasthan\n| pushpin_label_position  = right\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in Rajasthan, India\n| coordinates             = {{coord|23.55|N|74.45|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Rajasthan]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Banswara district|Banswara]]\n| established_title       = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| named_for               = \n| government_type         = nagar parishad\n| governing_body          = congress\n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = 302\n| population_total        = 100,128\n| population_as_of        = 2011\n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| demographics_type1      = Languages\n|demographics1_title2=Spoken\n|demographics1_info2=[[Wagdi language|Wagdi]]\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code             = 327001\n| area_code_type          = Telephone code\n| area_code               = 02962\n| registration_plate      = RJ-03\n| blank1_name_sec1        = [[Human sex ratio|Sex ratio]]\n| blank1_info_sec1        = 954 females per 1000 males\n| website                 = {{URL|http://banswara.rajasthan.gov.in/}}\n| iso_code                = [[ISO 3166-2:IN|RJ-IN]]\n| footnotes               =\n \n}}\n\n'''Banswara''' is a city in [[Banswara District]] in south [[Rajasthan]] in India. The state of [[Banswara State|Banswara]] was founded by Bansiya bhil. It is named for the \"bans\" or [[bamboo]] forests in the area..\n\nIt is also known as 'City of Hundred Islands' or 'CherraPoonji of Rajasthan', due to highest rain in [[Rajasthan]] and presence of numerous islands on the [[Mahi River]] named \"Chachakota\" where the islands located, which flows through Banswara. The city is governed by City Council (Nagar Parishad) which comes under Banswara Urban Agglomeration. The city has population of 100,128, its urban / metropolitan population is 101,177 of which 51,941 are males and 49,236 are females.<ref>{{cite web|title=Banswara District population|url=Parathapur disturbances in stock of big tea business, penalty recovery with tax of 11 lakhs|accessdate=27 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nBanswara is located at {{Coord|23.55|N|74.45|E|}}.<ref>[http://www.fallingrain.com/world/IN/24/Banswara.html Falling Rain Genomics, Inc \u2013 Banswara]</ref> It has an average elevation of 302&nbsp;metres (990&nbsp;ft).\n\n[[Banswara District]] is in southern Rajasthan with an area of {{convert|5999|km2|mi2}} located between 23.11\u00b0 N to 23.56\u00b0 N latitudes and 73.58\u00b0 E to 74.49\u00b0 E. longitudes. It is bounded on the north-east by Dhariawad, Pipalkoot & Arnod tehsils of Pratapgarh district of Rajasthan; on the east by Ratlam district of Madhya Pradesh; on the west by Sagwara and on north-west by Aspur tehsils of Dungarpur district of Rajasthan; on the south-east by Jhabua district of Madhya Pradesh and on south & south-west the Dohad district of Gujarat.\nThe region represents a rugged terrain undulated by short ridges west of Banswara. The eastern part of it is occupied by flat-topped hills of the Deccan trap. It has the southern end of the Aravali mountains. The drainage system belongs to the [[Mahi River|Mahi]] river which originates from Amjera hills near Dhar in Madhya Preadesh. Its main tributaries are Anas, Chanp, Erav, Hiran and Kagdi. The [[Mahi Bajaj Sagar Dam]] has been constructed on the Mahi, about {{convert|16|km|mi}} away from Banswara town. The Right and Left Main Canals and their distributaries irrigate {{convert|60149|ha|km2}} of land. Normal annual rainfall is about {{convert|82.59|cm|in}}.\n\nThe main crops are maize, wheat, rice, cotton soya bean and gram. Graphite, soapstone, dolomite, rock phosphate, limestone and a variety of marbles are mined in the region, with some deposits of gold found around Jagpura. About 20% of the area is designated as forested land, but most of the forest land is devoid of trees in the non-monsoon months.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://banswara.nic.in/e_geo.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-04-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721163344/http://www.banswara.nic.in/e_geo.htm |archivedate=2011-07-21 }}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n{{Main|Banswara State}}\nBanswara (literally \"the bamboo country\") was a Rajput feudatory state in [[Rajputana]] during [[British India]]. It borders [[Gujarat]] and is bounded on the north by the native states of [[Dungarpur]] and [[Udaipur]] or [[Mewar]]; on the northeast and east by [[Pratapgarh district, Rajasthan|Partapgarh]]; on the south by the dominions of [[Indore State|Holkar]] and the state of [[Jhabua State|Jabua]]; and on the west by the state of [[Rewa Kantha]].\n\nBanswara state was about {{convert|45|mi|km}} in length from north to south and {{convert|33|mi|km}} in breadth from east to west and had an area of {{convert|1606|mi2|km2}}.<ref>{{EB1911|inline=1|wstitle=Banswara|volume=3|page=355}}</ref> The population in 1941 was 258,760.<ref>{{cite web|title=Princely History of Banswara|url=http://princelystatesofindia.com/Princely/banswara.html|accessdate=3 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nBanswara district forms eastern part of the region known as [[Vagad]] or Vagwar. The district was formerly a state ruled by the Maharavals. It is said that a [[Bhil people|Bhil]] ruler Bansia or Wasna, ruled over it and Banswara was named after his name. Bansia was defeated and killed by Jagmal Singh who became the first Maharaval of the princely state. It is named so because of the '''[[bamboo]]''' ({{lang-hi|\u092c\u093e\u0902\u0938}}) which were found in abundance in the forests.\n\nBanswara massacre is also known as Rajasthan's \u2018[[Jallianwala Bagh massacre|Jallianwala Bagh]]\u2019, a little known event of the British Raj era.{{cn}}\n\nOn 17 November 1913, [[Banswara district]] of South Rajasthan was witness to a little-known massacre of around 1500 tribals by the British, echoing the [[Jallianwala Bagh massacre]] in which 329 people were killed in firing. British forces opened fire on tribals who had gathered on the Mangarh hillock situated in the [[Aravalli Range|Aravali]] mountains on the Rajasthan-Gujarat border. The tribals were led by their leader Govind Guru who inspired them to throw off the yoke of British rule.\n\nGovind Guru, influenced by social reformers like [[Dayananda Saraswati|Dayanand Saraswat]]<nowiki/>i, launched the 'Bhagat movement among the Bhils asking them to adhere to vegetarianism, and abstain from all types of intoxicants. The movement slowly took on a political hue and turned into a movement against the oppressive policies of the [[United Kingdom|British]].\n\nThe Bhils began opposing taxes imposed by the [[United Kingdom|British]] and forced labour imposed by the princely states of Banswara, [[Santrampur]], [[Dungarpur]] and [[Kushalgarh]]. Worried by the tribal revolt, the Britishers and princely states decided to crush the uprising. From October 1913, [[Govindguru|''Govind guru'']] asked his followers to gather at Mangarh hill from where they would conduct their operations.\n\nThe British asked them to vacate Mangarh hill by 15 November, but they refused. On 17 November, the tribals were gathering for a meeting when the British forces under Maj S Bailey and Capt E Stiley opened fire from cannons and guns on the crowd. Though there are no official estimates, locals say about 2500 people were killed in cold blood.\n\nGovind guru was captured and exiled from the area. He was imprisoned in [[Hyderabad]] jail and released in 1919 on grounds of good behavior. But as he was exiled from his homeland, he settled in [[Limdi]] in [[Gujarat]] where he died in 1931. The site of the massacre is today known as [[Mangarh Dham]] and the locals are demanding that a national memorial be built there in memory of the martyrs.\n\n== Tourism ==\n\n=== Andheswar Parshwanathji ===\n[[File:Andeshwar_Jain_Temple.JPG|thumb|Main idol at [[Andeshwar Parshwanath]] ]]\n[[Andeshwar Parshwanath]]ji is situated on a hillock in Kushalgarh tehsil of Banswara district. This is a famous Jain temple housing rare Shilalekhs of the 10th century. We could find two Digamabara Jain Parshwanatha temples at this place. The main temple was built by Digamabar Jain Panchayat of Kushalgarh.\n\n===Anekant Bahubali Temple Lohariya===\nAnekant Bahubali Temple is situated in Banswara-Udaipur Road in Lohariya Tehsil Ghari of Banswara District. This Jain temple is Famous for the 27-foot Standing Statue of Lord Bahubali which is made of White Sangmarar (marble). This Jain temple was made by the Inspiration of Digamber Acharya Shri 108 Bharat Sagarji maharaj here we can find many other temples of Jain Lords Like Panch Parmeshti Jinalay (tample), Manvadi Sapt charan Rishi's Tample, Adinatha Jinalaya etc. Has situated in The Campus of temple.\n\n=== Abdullah Pir ===\nAbdullah Pir is a Dargah of Sayedi Abdul Rasul Saheed, a Muslim saint and mostly visited by the Bohra Muslim. It's an important holy place for the Bohras. Abdullah Pir is located in the southern part of the city. On 10th Rabi' al-awwal, every year \"Urs\" is held at the Dargah. The people of the Bohara community take part in it in large numbers. This is a Muslim shrine of Dawoodi Bohras saint and is mostly visited by Dawoodi Bohra Muslims who visit this place during URS.\n\n=== Anand Sagar Lake ===\nThis artificial lake has been constructed by Lanchi Bai, the Rani of Maharval Jagami. It is also known as Bai Talab. Anand Sagar Lake is located on the eastern part of Banswara. It is enclosed by the holy trees named 'Kalpa Vriksha', famous for fulfilling the desire of the visitors. Nearby lies the chattris or cenotaphs of the rulers of the state.\n\n[[File: ARTHUNA TEMPLE.jpg|thumb]]\n\n=== Arthuna ===\nArthuna, as well as its surrounding areas, have clusters of ruined Hindu and Jain temples belonging to the 11th, 12th and the 15th centuries. Among the dilapidated ruins is a carved conjugated statue of Shiva, Parvati and Ganesh. Lankiya village around Arthuna has Shaivite temples called Nilkanth Mahadev Temples. The temple is an old stone temple having intricate carvings and sculpted figures of women embedded in the outer walls. The bull Nandi (Lord Shiva's faithful vehicle) stands guard at the entrance in the temple porch.<ref>http://techandtricki.com/banswara-tourism-tourist-places-in-banswara-rajasthan/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180109235540/http://techandtricki.com/banswara-tourism-tourist-places-in-banswara-rajasthan/ |date=9 January 2018 }} BANSWARA TOURISM</ref>\n\n=== Dailab Lake ===\nMorning [[aarti]] of Lord Hanuman followed by sunrise behind the hills with beautiful scenery through Dialab Lake can be observed at this Place. This place is situated on [[Pratapgarh district, Rajasthan|Pratapgarh]] Road, civil lines.  A well-made 'Harihar Maruti Dham' [[temple]] is situated near this lake. A popular place for devotees of [[Hanuman|Lord Hanuman]] during the day of [[Hanuman Jayanti]]. \n\nIn recent years water hyacinth has invaded whole lake which disappoints its visitors. Many steps haven been taken to remove this weed but all resulted failures.\n\n=== Madareshwar Temple ===\nBanswara has a number of ancient Hindu and Jain temples, and in the past was known as Lodi Kashi or the city of temples. This famous temple of Lord Shiva is situated inside the natural cave of a high hill on the eastern part of the city. It presents a sensational natural view. The cave temple provides an Amarnath Yatra like feeling to the pilgrims, due to its typical location.\n\n=== Mahi Dam ===\nMahi Dam is one of the major attractions of Banswara. It is situated 16 kilometres from Banswara town in Banswara district Rajasthan, India. The dam was constructed between 1972 and 1983 under the Mahi Bajaj Sagar Project, for the purposes of hydroelectric power generation and water supply.various dams and canals have been constructed over an enticingly enchanting scenic surrounding. Near the dam, you could locate the enticing garden with fountain. It is the second largest dam in Rajasthan.\n\n=== Mangarh Dham ===\nThis is an important fair of the tribals and is held on Margshirsha Purnima. At this fair the tribals of [[Rajasthan]], [[Madhya Pradesh]] &\n[[Gujarat]] participate and they pay tribute to Guru [[Govindgiri]], founder of the Samp sabha.\n\n=== Paraheada ===\nParaheada is located in the Garhi Tehsil. It is famous temple of Lord Shiva. It was constructed by the Mandlik. Paraheada is 22&nbsp;km from Banswara.\nShri Raj Mandir or more popularly known as the City Palace was built in the 16th century and situated on a hillock overlooking the town. Covering a huge area it follows typical style of old Rajput architecture. Though lack of funds has made many royal palaces of Rajasthan exchange hands with the government after Independence, this palace is still owned by the Royal family\n\n=== Bhim kund ===\nIt is a place surrounded by hills. People call it \"Phati Khan\" because it is a deep cave under a hill. There is a pool of very cold water which is found throughout the year. It is said that Lord Ram, during his exile came and stayed here for some time.\n\n=== Talwada ===\nTalwara is another place to visit near Banswara. Its historical significance due to its primeval temples and the devastated of some old monuments. Talwara is the temples of Sun, Lord Amaliya Ganesh, Laxmi Narayan Temple, and Jain Temple of Sambhavnath make Talwara a religiously important site. The idols in these temples are carved in local black stone.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\n=== Kupda ===\n\nkupda is another place to visit near Banswara. It is famous temple of VEJVA MATA. Temple is situated in Banswara-Dungarpur Road near mayur mill.\n\n=== Tripura Sundari ===\n[[File:Shri tripura sundari temple.JPG|thumb|Shri Tripura Sundari Temple]]\nTripura Sundari is the temple, devoted to Goddess Tripura Sundari or Turita Mata. This temple has a gorgeous idol of black stone having 18 hands and more important each hand carrying a different emblem. The Goddess is seen riding a tiger. It is believed that its one of the Shakti Peeths of Hindus having divine powers. It is believed that this temple was built before Samrat Kanishka, who rule here. The exact date of its construction is not yet known. It is said to be one of the \"Shakti Peeths\" of the Hindus having charismatic divine power. But it is believed that the temple was constructed approximately before the reign of the Kushana emperor Kanishka who ruled here in the first century AD.\n\n=== Sai Tample ===\nSai tample is most viewed place in banswara, This is the temple of god Sai baba. The Om Sri Shirdi Sai Baba temple established in 2004. This temple is not only settled you with peace of mind but also providing the dish of love who is visiting here on Thursday by the trust.<ref>patrika.com/banswara-news/banswara-sai-baba-temple-every-thrusday-bhandara-2633115/</ref> This temple has a big size idol of white stone of [[Sai Baba of Shirdi|''Sai baba'']] and also one god ganesh, This temple have unique ''[[rangoli]]'' of stone inside temple, and a big jhumar light on roof, there's a big open place in front of temple\n\nOne side of this temple one big pyramid hall, and one statue of [[Mahavira|''Mahaveer swami'']] .From this side we watch one [http://hi.krishnakosh.org/%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%83%E0%A4%B7%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%A3/%E0%A4%A4%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%B0%E0%A4%BF%E0%A4%B6%E0%A5%82%E0%A4%B2_%E0%A4%85%E0%A4%B8%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%A4%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%B0 ''Trishul''] , and [[Om|''\u0950'']] sign which made by stones on mountains.\n\nOther side open place which have children's play items like Jhula, slides etc. and also view of water of [http://india-wris.nrsc.gov.in/wrpinfo/index.php?title=Kagdi_Weir_W00133 ''Kagdi pick up weir''] also one statue of [[State Emblem of India]]\n\n== Location ==\n\nThe Banswara district lies in the southernmost part of [[Rajasthan]]. It is surrounded by [[Pratapgarh, Rajasthan|Pratapgarh]] in the north, [[Dungarpur]] in the west, [[Ratlam]] and [[Jhabua]] districts of [[Madhya Pradesh]] in the east and south and [[Dahod district]], [[Gujarat]] to the south.\n\n=== Distance from major cities ===\n\nThe closest major city to Banswara is [[Udaipur]] which is 165&nbsp;km away. [[Indore]] and [[Ahmedabad]] are also close, at 215&nbsp;km and 245&nbsp;km away respectively. The [[town]] is 827&nbsp;km from [[New Delhi]] and 710&nbsp;km from [[Mumbai]].\n\n== Development and technical education ==\n\nSince 2012 Government engineering College has been started and in State Budget of 2013\u201314 declared for Starting of one Medical college in Banswara .{{when|date=October 2012}}\n\nFor opening of one [[Nuclear power|nuclear]] power plant, & Two Super critical thermal power plant & Railway line ([[Ratlam district|Ratlam]] -[[Dungarpur district|Dungarpur]] via [[Banswara district|Banswara]]) various Proceeding of State Govt is going on.{{when|date=October 2012}}\n\n== Demographics ==\n{{bar box\n|title=Religions in Banswara\n|titlebar=#Fcd116\n|left1=Religion\n|right1=Percent\n|float=right\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|[[Hindus]]|orange|64.83}}\n{{bar percent|[[Muslims]]|green|26.32}}\n}}\n{{As of|2001}} India [[census]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.net/results/town.php?stad=A&state5=999|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040616075334/http://www.censusindia.net/results/town.php?stad=A&state5=999|archivedate=2004-06-16|title= Census of India 2001: Data from the 2001 Census, including cities, villages and towns (Provisional)|accessdate=2008-11-01|publisher= Census Commission of India}}</ref> Banswara city had a population of 101,177. Males constitute 51% of the population and females 49%. Banswara city has an average literacy rate of 86.98%, higher than the national average of 59.5%, with 92.76% of the males and 81.01% of females literate.\n\n== Culture ==\n[[File:Kangra pick up weir.jpg|thumb|Kagdi Pick Up Weir]]\nSituated amidst the [[Aravali Range|Aravali]] valley, Banswara represents tribal culture in Rajasthan. With a landscape predominated by bamboo trees ({{lang-hi|\u092c\u093e\u0901\u0938}}) the region came to be known as Banswara. Banswara town was founded by King Jagmal Singh.<ref>{{cite web|title=Banswara District |url=http://banswara.nic.in/e_culture.htm |publisher=NIC |accessdate=3 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120418062809/http://banswara.nic.in/e_culture.htm |archivedate=18 April 2012 }}</ref> The town has eleven and a half Swayambhoo [[Shivalinga]]s; it was also called 'Lodhikashi' or little [[Varanasi|Kashi]].  Yet another name is 'An Area of Hundred Islands'. Situated in southern Rajasthan, the town borders [[Gujarat]] and [[Madhya Pradesh]]. Due to this inter-regional neighborhood, the Vagdi culture has emerged as a mixture of Gujarati, Malwi, Rajasthani and Mewari cultures.  Banswara district is rich in forests, hills and wildlife.  Tribals are the natives of this region.\n\n== Climate and rainfall ==\n\nThe district has a climate which is milder than that in the desert regions in further north and north-west.\n* Maximum temperature is 45 degrees Celsius to 46 degrees Celsius.\n* Minimum temperature is 10 degrees Celsius to 20 degrees Celsius\n* Normal annual rainfall is 922.4&nbsp;mm\n\n== Civic administration ==\n[[Banswara Municipal Board]] has been upgraded to Municipal council (Nagar Parishad).\n\n== Government and politics ==\n\nIn 2018 the MLA of this region is [Arjun Singh Bamaniya].\n\nHaridev Joshi belong to a village name Khandu in Banswara district remained chief minister of Rajasthan 3 times. Under haridev Joshi Banswara seen lots of development most prominent one was construnction of Mahi Bajaj Sagar dam which transformed the economy and living standard of whole district.\n\n== Utility services ==\nThe total transformer capacity in the district is 63.1 MV\u00b7A. Of the 1,431 villages 1,219 villages were electrified up to 31 March 2000.\n\nThe [[Mahi river]] flows on the borders of Peepalkhoot and Ghatol and Banswara Panchayat Samitis. The Mahi project has the capacity to irrigate an area of 800 square kilometres.\n\n== Transport ==\n\n=== Road ===\n\nRoad transport is the only mode of goods and passengers movement from and to the district. The district headquarters has direct road connection with [[Ratlam]], [[Dungarpur]], [[Dahod]] and [[Jaipur]]. Total road length in the district is 1,747&nbsp;km, as of 31 March 2000.\n\n=== Rail ===\n\nThe Railway Ministry has approved railway line to be established to connect the [[Dungarpur]] and [[Ratlam]] station. The total distance between Ratlam to Dungarpur is around 187.6&nbsp;km (116.56&nbsp;mi), Banswara is situated in the centre of these two stations. Recently railway line work in progress and final location for rail track marked by agency.\n\n=== Air ===\n\nThe nearest airport is at [[Udaipur]] {{convert|165|km|mi}}, where there is a helipad and runways for charter planes to Talwada village airstrip around {{convert|13|km|mi}} from Banswara city. There is no airport at Banswara itself, but nearby at Udaipur {{convert|160|km|mi}}, Indore (Madhya Pradesh) {{convert|212|km|mi}} & Ahmedabad (Guj) {{convert|285|km|mi}} are major airports close to Banswara.\n\n== Education ==\n\nSchools and higher educational institutions in Banswara are administered either by the Directorate of Education, the government, or private organizations. In 2008\u201309, there were 1,995 primary and middle schools, 283 secondary and senior secondary schools in the city. The higher education institutions in the city included Two Govt P.G.Colleges and & Eight Private colleges .For Technical education one Govt. POLYTECHNIC & one Govt. ENGINEERING COLLEGE & Two ITIs.\n\nPrivate schools in the city\u2014which employ either English or Hindi as the language of instruction\u2014are affiliated to one of two administering bodies: the [[Rajasthan Board of Secondary Education]] and the [[Central Board for Secondary Education]].\n\nsome school for example:- Kendriya vidyalaya, St. Paul senior secondary school, Ankur senior secondary school,\n\n== Media ==\n\nThe focus on political reportage, including regular television broadcasts of Indian parliament sessions. Many country-wide media agencies, among them the state-owned [[Press Trust of India]] and [[Doordarshan]], are based in the city. Television programming in the city includes two free terrestrial television channels offered by Doordarshan, and several Hindi, English and regional-languages cable channels offered by multi-system operators. Satellite television, in contrast, is yet to gain large-scale subscribership in the city.\n\nPrint journalism remains a popular news medium. During the year 2005\u201306, newspapers\u2014in Hindi languages\u2014were published from the city. Of these, Hindi language newspapers, and included [[Dainik Bhaskar]], [[Rajasthan Patrika]]. Other major English newspapers include ''[[Indian Express]]'', ''[[Business Standard]]'', ''[[The Times of India]]'', ''[[The Hindu]]''.\n\n== Notable people ==\n*[[Haridev Joshi]], former Chief Minister of Rajasthan\n*[[Imam Siddique]], Big Boss Runner Up\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Banswara district}}\n{{Rajasthan}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Banswara district]]\n[[Category:Cities in Malwa]]\n", "name_user": "NitinMlk", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Banswara"}
{"title_page": "Kalyan Singh Gupta", "text_new": "{{Use Indian English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                    = Kalyan Singh Gupta\n| image                   = \n| imagesize               = \n| caption                 = \n| birth_date              = 1923\n| birth_place             = Haryana, India\n| death_date              = 23 January 2002\n| death_place             = [[New Delhi]], India\n| restingplace            = \n| restingplacecoordinates = \n| othername               = \n| occupation              = Social worker, independence activist\n| yearsactive             = \n| known for               = \n| spouse                  = \n| domesticpartner         = \n| children                = \n| parents                 = \n| website                 = \n| awards                  = [[Padma Shri]]\n}}\n\n'''Kalyan Singh Gupta''' (1923\u20132002) was an Indian independence activist and social worker.<ref name=\"Tribune India\">{{cite web | url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2002/20020125/nation.htm#7 | title=Tribune India | publisher=Tribune India | date=24 January 2002 | accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref> He is the co-founder of the ''Lok Kalyan Samiti'',<ref name=\"LKS\">{{cite web | url=http://www.lokkalyansamiti.in/Default.aspx | title=LKS | publisher=Lok Kalyan Samiti | date=2015 | accessdate=13 May 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150212105141/http://lokkalyansamiti.in/Default.aspx | archive-date=12 February 2015 | url-status=dead }}</ref> a [[non governmental organization|non-governmental organization]] based in the [[National Capital Region (India)|National Capital Region]], together with [[Sucheta Kripalani]] in 1952.<ref name=\"IIT Delhi Alumni Association\">{{cite web | url=http://iitdalumni.com/news/lok-kalyan-samiti-headed-ms-harita-gupta-wins-national-award-2009-work-area-child-welfare | title=IIT Delhi Alumni Association | publisher=IIT Delhi Alumni Association | date=14 November 2010 | accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"LKS About US\">{{cite web | url=http://www.lokkalyansamiti.in/About.aspx | title=LKS About US | publisher=LKS | date=2015 | accessdate=13 May 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150212181531/http://lokkalyansamiti.in/About.aspx | archive-date=12 February 2015 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nBorn in 1923 in the Indian state of [[Haryana]], he completed his early college education in [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] and [[Delhi]] during which he took part in the [[Indian independence movement]] and later, joined the [[London School of Economics]] to secure a master's degree studying under the tutelage of [[Harold Laski]].<ref name=\"Tribune India\" /> Returning to India in 1951, he started his career as a journalist at the India News Chronicle.<ref name=\"Tribune India\" /> A year later, he founded Lok Kalyan Samiti, along with [[Sucheta Kripalani]].<ref name=\"Tribune India\" /> He also started the ''Central Relief Committee'' (CRC India) in 1959 for providing relief aid to the Tibetan refugees.<ref name=\"Tribune India\" /> He was honoured by the [[Government of India]] in 1969, with the award of [[Padma Shri]], the fourth highest Indian civilian award.<ref name=\"Padma Shri\">{{cite web|url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |title=Padma Shri |publisher=Padma Shri |date=2015 |accessdate=11 November 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6U68ulwpb?url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |archivedate=15 November 2014 }}</ref>\n\nKalyan Singh Gupta died on 23 January 2002 at New Delhi at the age of 79.<ref name=\"Tribune India\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{portal|India}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gupta, Kalyan Singh}}\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Shri in social work]]\n[[Category:Indian male social workers]]\n[[Category:1923 births]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:Indian independence activists from Haryana]]\n[[Category:Indian male journalists]]\n[[Category:Gandhians]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Haryana]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:Social workers from Haryana]]\n\n\n{{India-activist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use Indian English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                    = Kalyan Singh Gupta\n| image                   = \n| imagesize               = \n| caption                 = \n| birth_date              = 1923\n| birth_place             = Haryana, India\n| death_date              = 23 January 2002\n| death_place             = [[New Delhi]], India\n| restingplace            = \n| restingplacecoordinates = \n| othername               = \n| occupation              = Social worker, independence activist\n| yearsactive             = \n| known for               = \n| spouse                  = \n| domesticpartner         = \n| children                = \n| parents                 = \n| website                 = \n| awards                  = [[Padma Shri]]\n}}\n\n'''Kalyan Singh Gupta''' (1923\u20132002) was an Indian independence activist and social worker.<ref name=\"Tribune India\">{{cite web | url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2002/20020125/nation.htm#7 | title=Tribune India | publisher=Tribune India | date=24 January 2002 | accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref> He is the co-founder of the ''Lok Kalyan Samiti'',<ref name=\"LKS\">{{cite web | url=http://www.lokkalyansamiti.in/Default.aspx | title=LKS | publisher=Lok Kalyan Samiti | date=2015 | accessdate=13 May 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150212105141/http://lokkalyansamiti.in/Default.aspx | archive-date=12 February 2015 | url-status=dead }}</ref> a [[non governmental organization|non-governmental organization]] based in the [[National Capital Region (India)|National Capital Region]], together with [[Sucheta Kripalani]] in 1952.<ref name=\"IIT Delhi Alumni Association\">{{cite web | url=http://iitdalumni.com/news/lok-kalyan-samiti-headed-ms-harita-gupta-wins-national-award-2009-work-area-child-welfare | title=IIT Delhi Alumni Association | publisher=IIT Delhi Alumni Association | date=14 November 2010 | accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"LKS About US\">{{cite web | url=http://www.lokkalyansamiti.in/About.aspx | title=LKS About US | publisher=LKS | date=2015 | accessdate=13 May 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150212181531/http://lokkalyansamiti.in/About.aspx | archive-date=12 February 2015 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nBorn in 1923 in the Indian state of [[Haryana]], he completed his early college education in [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] and [[Delhi]] during which he took part in the [[Indian independence movement]] and later, joined the [[London School of Economics]] to secure a master's degree studying under the tutelage of [[Harold Laski]].<ref name=\"Tribune India\" /> Returning to India in 1951, he started his career as a journalist at the India News Chronicle.<ref name=\"Tribune India\" /> A year later, he founded Lok Kalyan Samiti, along with [[Sucheta Kripalani]].<ref name=\"Tribune India\" /> He also started the ''Central Relief Committee'' (CRC India) in 1959 for providing relief aid to the Tibetan refugees.<ref name=\"Tribune India\" /> He was honoured by the [[Government of India]] in 1969, with the award of [[Padma Shri]], the fourth highest Indian civilian award.<ref name=\"Padma Shri\">{{cite web|url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |title=Padma Shri |publisher=Padma Shri |date=2015 |accessdate=11 November 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6U68ulwpb?url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |archivedate=15 November 2014 }}</ref>\n\nKalyan Singh Gupta died on 23 January 2002 at New Delhi at the age of 79.<ref name=\"Tribune India\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{portal|India}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gupta, Kalyan Singh}}\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Shri in social work]]\n[[Category:Indian male social workers]]\n[[Category:1923 births]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:Indian independence activists from Haryana]]\n[[Category:Indian male journalists]]\n[[Category:Gandhians]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Haryana]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:Social workers from Haryana]]\n\n\n{{India-activist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kalyan_Singh_Gupta"}
{"title_page": "Henry Cejudo", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{short description|American Olympic wrestler and mixed martial arts fighter}}\n{{Infobox martial artist\n| name            = Henry Cejudo\n| other_names     = The Messenger\n                  \n                  \n                  King of Cringe\n                  Triple C\n| image           = Henry Cejudo smiling.jpg\n| image_size      =\n| alt             = \n| caption         = Cejudo interviewed in 2018\n| birth_name      = \n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1987|02|9}}\n| birth_place     = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], United States\n| death_date      = \n| death_place     = \n| death_cause     = \n| residence       = \n| nationality     = American\n| ethnicity       = \n| height          = 5 ft 4 in<ref name=UFC188fighterstats>{{cite web |url=http://www.ufc.com/event/UFC188/printFightCard |title=Fight Card \u2013 UFC 188 Velasquez vs. Werdum |publisher=UFC.com |accessdate=June 14, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150613034707/http://www.ufc.com/event/UFC188/printFightCard |archive-date=June 13, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| weight          = 135lb\n| weight_class    = [[Flyweight (MMA)|Flyweight]] <br>[[Bantamweight (MMA)|Bantamweight]] \n| reach           = 64 in<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.espn.com/extra/mma/playercard?playerId=3023388&src=desktop|title = Henry Cejudo MMA Stats}}</ref>\n| style           = [[Wrestling]]\n| stance          = \n| fighting_out_of = [[Phoenix, Arizona]], United States\n| team            = Fight Ready\n| trainer         = [[Eric Albarracin]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2019/2/8/18212505/captain-eric-takes-a-victory-lap|title=Captain Eric takes a victory lap|author=Chuck Mindenhall|date=February 8, 2019|publisher=mmafighting.com}}</ref>\n| rank            = Yellow belt in [[Shotokan|Shotokan Karate]]<ref>https://conandaily.com/2019/01/20/ufc-flyweight-champion-henry-cejudo-beats-tj-dillashaw-dedicates-ufc-fight-night-143-win-to-all-flyweights/</ref>\n| wrestling       = [[Wrestling at the 2008 Summer Olympics|Olympic gold medalist]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.teamusa.org/usa-wrestling/athletes/Henry-Cejudo |title=Henry Cejudo |publisher=teamusa.org |accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref>\n| years_active    = 2013\u2013present\n| mma_kowin       = 7\n| mma_subwin      =\n| mma_decwin      = 8\n| mma_koloss      = 1\n| mma_subloss     = \n| mma_decloss     = 1\n| mma_draw        = \n| mma_nc          = \n| university      = \n| school          = \n| url             = \n| sherdog         = 125297\n| footnotes       = \n| updated         = \n| medaltemplates      = \n{{Medal|Sport | Men's [[freestyle wrestling]] }}\n{{MedalCountry | {{USA}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Olympic Games]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[2008 Summer Olympics|2008 Beijing]] | [[Wrestling at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle 55 kg|55 kg]] }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Wrestling World Cup]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| 2007 Krasnoyarsk |55 kg}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Pan American Games]] }}\n{{Medal|Gold | [[2007 Pan American Games|2007 Rio de Janeiro]] | [[Wrestling at the 2007 Pan American Games|55 kg]] }}\n{{MedalCompetition | Pan American Championships}}\n{{MedalGold| 2008 Colorado Springs|55 kg}}\n{{MedalGold| 2007 San Salvador|55 kg}}\n{{MedalGold| 2006 Rio de Janeiro|55 kg}}\n}}\n\n'''Henry Carlos Cejudo''' (born February 9, 1987) is an American [[Mixed martial arts|mixed martial artist]] and former [[Freestyle wrestling|freestyle wrestler]]. He is currently signed to the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] (UFC) and is the former [[UFC Flyweight Championship| UFC flyweight champion]] and current [[UFC Bantamweight Championship| UFC bantamweight champion]]. He is the fourth person to hold titles in two different weight classes simultaneously. As a freestyle wrestler, Cejudo is an [[Wrestling at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle 55 kg|Olympic gold medalist]]. As of August 19, 2019, he is #3 in the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship rankings#Pound-for-pound|UFC men's pound-for-pound rankings]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ufc.com/rankings|title=Rankings {{!}} UFC|website=www.ufc.com|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nCejudo was born in Los Angeles, California USA. Both his parents were born in [[Mexico City]], [[Mexico]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/boxing/la-sp-ufc-227-cejudo-20180803-story.html|title=Henry Cejudo the gold medallist returns to his L.A. stomping grounds facing the toughest of tests in Demetrious Johnson - Los Angeles Times|last=Pugmire|first=Lance|website=latimes.com|access-date=November 8, 2018}}</ref> He is one of seven children.\n\nCejudo's parents were both undocumented immigrants and he moved nearly 50 times as a child. After his parents separated when he was four, Cejudo's mother moved the family to New Mexico, and two years later, to Arizona. Cejudo also never slept alone in his own bed until he was provided one by U.S.A. Wrestling while participating in a residency program at the U.S. Olympic training facility. Henry also won the Arizona state golden gloves in boxing. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/dailyfix/2008/08/20/born-to-illegal-immigrants-henry-cejudo-wins-gold-for-us/|title=Born to Illegal Immigrants, Henry Cejudo the gold medallist Wins Gold for U.S.|last1=Bialik|first1=Carl|publisher=The Wall Street Journal|date=August 20, 2008|accessdate=January 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2008-aug-20-sp-olyplaschke20-story.html</ref>\n\n==Wrestling career==\n\nInspired by his older brother Angel, who was a four-time state champion with a record of 150 wins and zero defeats,<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/20/sports/olympics/20cejudo.html</ref> Henry also became a four-time high school state champion. His freshman and sophomore year titles were won in Arizona, before he moved to Colorado Springs, Colorado, to become a resident athlete at the U.S. Olympic Training Center. He won the Colorado state high school championships as a junior and senior, and was named ASICS National High School Wrestler of the Year in 2006. In the same year, he was selected in the Wrestling USA Magazine\u2019s Dream Team of High School All-Americans.  <ref>https://www.teamusa.org/USA-Wrestling/Features/2018/June/01/Hall-of-Fame-biography-Henry-Cejudo-Distinguished-Member |=September 26, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, while still in high school, Cejudo won the [[USA Wrestling]] national freestyle championship.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wrestling.teamusa.org/athlete/athlete/1118 |title=USA Wrestling \u2013 Features, Events, Results \u2013 Team USA |work=Team USA |accessdate=December 14, 2014}}</ref> Soon after his victory, he began full-time training at the [[United States Olympic Training Center]] in [[Colorado Springs, Colorado]].<ref>[http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5gccNXZMsqbKDhQkfpNrpXKy6RWCAD92L9EFO1]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080822171704/http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5gccNXZMsqbKDhQkfpNrpXKy6RWCAD92L9EFO1 |date=August 22, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nFollowing successful performances at the [[Pan American Games]] and Pan American Championships, Cejudo won a gold medal at the [[Wrestling at the 2008 Summer Olympics|2008 Summer Olympics in Beijing]]. At the time, he was the youngest American to become an Olympic champion in freestyle wrestling.<ref>http://www.timesleader.com/sports/Cejudo_rsquo_s_freestyle_wrestling_gold_turns_out_to_be_surprise_story_of_the_day_08-20-2008.html</ref> After the 2008 Beijing Olympics, Cejudo took an extended break from competition, before retiring from freestyle wrestling in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/olympics/wrestling/story/_/id/7842927/2012-london-olympics-henry-cejudo-retires-falling-short-wrestling-trials|title=Drehs: Cejudo retires after falling short at wrestling trials|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Mixed martial arts career==\n===Early career===\nOn January 30, 2013, Cejudo announced on his Twitter page that he planned to begin training for a career in MMA.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/HenryCejudo/status/296658470705438720 |title=Henry Cejudo on Twitter |work=Twitter |accessdate=December 14, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/blog/Olympic-Gold-Medalist-Henry-Cejudo-MMA-Here-I-Come-49561 |title=Olympic Gold Medalist Henry Cejudo: \u2018MMA, Here I Come!\u2019 |work=Sherdog |accessdate=December 14, 2014}}</ref> Despite wrestling at 121 pounds during his wrestling career, Cejudo fought at 135 pounds in his MMA debut.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmajunkie.com/news/2013/01/olympic-gold-medalist-henry-cejudo-to-fight-at-135-for-spring-mma-debut |title=Olympic gold medalist Henry Cejudo to fight at 135 in spring MMA debut |work=MMAjunkie |accessdate=December 14, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130914104756/http://www.mmajunkie.com/news/2013/01/olympic-gold-medalist-henry-cejudo-to-fight-at-135-for-spring-mma-debut |archivedate=September 14, 2013 }}</ref> He defeated Michael Poe by TKO due to punches in his MMA debut on March 2, 2013, for the Arizona-based World Fighting Federation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/Olympic-Gold-Medalist-Henry-Cejudo-Cruises-in-MMA-Debut-at-World-Fighting-Federation-50577 |title=Olympic Gold Medalist Henry Cejudo Cruises in MMA Debut at World Fighting Federation |work=Sherdog |accessdate=December 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOver the next year, Cejudo amassed a record of 6-0 with three wins by TKO, one by submission, and two by decision. Prior to signing with the UFC, Cejudo was listed as the #1 ranked bantamweight prospect in the MMA Prospects Report 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rankingmma.com/henry-cejudo-mma-prospects-report-2013/ |title=Henry Cejudo : MMA Prospects Report 2013 |author=D.C. Ross |work=Ranking MMA |accessdate=December 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Ultimate Fighting Championship===\nOn July 25, 2014, Cejudo signed with the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship|UFC]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bloodyelbow.com/2014/7/25/5938707/ufc-signs-olympic-gold-medalist-henry-cejudo |title=UFC signs Olympic gold medalist Henry Cejudo |work=Bloody Elbow |accessdate=December 14, 2014}}</ref> He is the third Olympic gold medalist wrestler in company history, after [[Mark Schultz (wrestler)|Mark Schultz]] and [[Kevin Jackson]].<ref>{{cite web |title=UFC Olympic Gold medailst wrestlers |url=http://www.ufc.com/news/Cejudo-Chases-a-New-Kind-of-Gold |accessdate=August 28, 2014}}</ref> Cejudo was expected to face [[Scott Jorgensen]] on August 30, 2014, at [[UFC 177]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cagepotato.com/henry-cejudo-signs-with-the-ufc-will-meet-scott-jorgensen-at-ufc-177/ |title=Henry Cejudo Signs With the UFC, Will Meet Scott Jorgensen at UFC 177 |publisher=cagepotato.com |author= |accessdate=July 25, 2014 |date=July 25, 2014}}</ref> However, due to medical issues on the day of the weigh-ins, Cejudo was forced out of the bout and the fight was subsequently canceled.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/2014/08/medical-issue-forces-henry-cejudo-out-of-ufc-177-fight-with-scott-jorgensen |title=Medical issue forces Henry Cejudo out of UFC 177 fight with Scott Jorgensen |publisher=mmajunkie.com |author= |accessdate=August 29, 2014 |date=August 29, 2014}}</ref> In light of this, and his history of missing weight, president [[Dana White]] said Cejudo had to move up to bantamweight or leave the UFC.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/Former-Olympian-Henry-Cejudo-Must-Move-to-135-to-Continue-Fighting-in-the-UFC-73007 |title=Former Olympian Henry Cejudo must move to 135 to continue fighting in the UFC |work=Sherdog.com |accessdate=December 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn his eventual debut, Cejudo faced [[Dustin Kimura]] in a bantamweight bout on December 13, 2014, at [[UFC on Fox 13]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2014/10/20/7022971/henry-cejudo-meets-dustin-kimura-in-ufc-on-fox-13-bantamweight-bout |title=Henry Cejudo meets Dustin Kimura in UFC on FOX 13 bantamweight bout |publisher=mmafighting.com |author=Dave Doyle |accessdate=October 20, 2014 |date=October 20, 2014}}</ref> Cejudo won the fight by unanimous decision.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/2014/12/ufc-on-fox-13-results-henry-cejudo-outboxes-dustin-kimura-for-debut-win |title=UFC on FOX 13 results: Henry Cejudo outboxes Dustin Kimura for debut win |work=mmajunkie.com |author=Ben Fowlkes |date=December 13, 2014 |accessdate=December 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nCejudo faced [[Chris Cariaso]] in a flyweight bout on March 14, 2015, at [[UFC 185]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/Chris-CariasoHenry-Cejudo-Flyweight-Bout-Added-to-UFC-185-80189 |title=Chris Cariaso-Henry Cejudo flyweight bout added to UFC 185 |publisher=sherdog.com |author=Staff |date=January 12, 2015 |accessdate=January 12, 2015}}</ref> He won the fight by unanimous decision.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/2015/03/ufc-185-results-photos-henry-cejudo-grinds-out-chris-cariaso-in-official-flyweight-debut |title=UFC 185 results, photos: Henry Cejudo grinds out Chris Cariaso in official flyweight debut |publisher=mmajunkie.com |author=Steven Marrocco |date=March 14, 2015 |accessdate=March 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nCejudo faced [[Chico Camus]] on June 13, 2015, at [[UFC 188]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmamania.com/2015/4/24/8494519/ufc-188-henry-cejudo-vs-chico-camus-official-for-june-13-ppv-in-mexico |title=UFC 188: Henry Cejudo vs. Chico Camus official for June 13 PPV in Mexico |publisher=mmamania.com |author=Alex Schlinsky |date=April 24, 2015 |accessdate=April 24, 2015}}</ref> He won the fight by unanimous decision.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/ufc-188-results-henry-cejudo-remains-undefeated-decision-022154314--mma.html |title=Henry Cejudo remains undefeated with decision over Chico Camus |publisher=mmaweekly.com |author=Staff |date=June 13, 2015 |accessdate=June 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nCejudo was briefly linked to a bout against former title challenger [[Joseph Benavidez]] on September 5, 2015, at [[UFC 191]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmasucka.com/2015/07/11/joseph-benavidez-takes-on-henry-cejudo-in-september/ |title=Joseph Benavidez takes on Henry Cejudo in September |publisher=mmasucka.com |author=Jeremy Brand |date=July 11, 2015 |accessdate=July 11, 2015}}</ref> However, the fight did not take place at the event. In turn, Cejudo faced [[Jussier Formiga]] on November 21, 2015, at [[UFC Fight Night 78|The Ultimate Fighter Latin America 2 Finale]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://themmacorner.com/2015/08/17/henry-cejudo-vs-jussier-formiga-booked-for-tuf-latin-america-2-finale-in-mexico/ |title=Henry Cejudo vs. \u2018Jussier\u2019 Formiga Booked for TUF Latin America 2 Finale in Mexico |publisher=themmacorner.com |author=Jos\u00e9 Youngs |date=August 17, 2015 |accessdate=August 17, 2015}}</ref>  He won the fight by split decision.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/2015/11/ufc-fight-night-78-results-henry-cejudo-gets-strange-split-decision-over-jussier-formiga |title=UFC Fight Night 78 results: Henry Cejudo gets strange split decision over Jussier Formiga |publisher=mmajunkie.com |author=Brent Brookhouse |date=November 21, 2015 |accessdate=November 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn September 16, 2015, Cejudo announced that he would refuse to fight in Nevada after the Nevada State Athletic Commission suspended and fined Nick Diaz following a failed drug test at [[UFC 182]]. Cejudo cited the NSAC's process in determining Diaz's guilt as the reason for the boycott.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmamania.com/2015/9/16/9338625/ufc-henry-cejudo-refuses-to-fight-nevada-in-wake-of-nick-diaz-suspension-mma|title=Henry Cejudo refuses to fight in Nevada in wake of Nick Diaz suspension|publisher=mmamania.com|author=Adam Guillen Jr|date=September 16, 2015|accessdate=April 24, 2016}}</ref>  Despite the lack of change in NSAC procedure, Cejudo ended his Nevada boycott to face UFC Flyweight champion [[Demetrious Johnson (fighter)|Demetrious Johnson]] on April 23, 2016, at [[UFC 197]] for the Flyweight title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/Demetrious-Johnson-to-Defend-Flyweight-Crown-vs-Henry-Cejudo-at-UFC-197-99875|title=Demetrious Johnson to defend flyweight crown vs. Henry Cejudo at UFC 197|publisher=sherdog.com|author=Tristen Critchfield|date=February 6, 2016|accessdate=February 6, 2016}}</ref> He lost the fight via TKO in the first round, being dropped with a variety of strikes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2016/4/24/11496620/ufc-197-results-demetrious-johnson-steamrolls-henry-cejudo|title=UFC 197 results: Demetrious Johnson steamrolls Henry Cejudo|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Dave Doyle|date=April 23, 2016|accessdate=April 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, the UFC announced that Cejudo would be one of the coaches, opposite [[Joseph Benavidez]] on [[The Ultimate Fighter: Tournament of Champions|The Ultimate Fighter 24]]. The pairing faced each other on December 3, 2016, at [[The Ultimate Fighter: Tournament of Champions#The Ultimate Fighter 24 Finale|The Ultimate Fighter 24 Finale]].<ref name=\"TUF24\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/Joseph-Benavidez-Henry-Cejudo-to-Serve-as-Coaches-on-The-Ultimate-Fighter-24-104813|title=Joseph Benavidez, Henry Cejudo to serve as coaches on \u2018The Ultimate Fighter 24\u2019|publisher=sherdog.com|author=Tristen Critchfield|date=May 11, 2016|accessdate=May 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ufc.com/news/Flyweights-to-be-featured-on-Season-24-of-TUF|title=Flyweights to be featured on The Ultimate Fighter Season 24|publisher=ufc.com|author=Thomas Gerbasi|date=May 11, 2016|accessdate=May 11, 2016}}</ref> Cejudo lost the back-and-forth fight via split decision.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mma/story/_/id/18197417/joseph-benavidez-edges-henry-cejudo-ufc-tuf-24-finale-mma|title=Joseph Benavidez edges Henry Cejudo at TUF 24 Finale|publisher=espn.com|author=Brett Okamoto|date=December 3, 2016|accessdate=December 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nCejudo was expected to face [[Sergio Pettis]] on May 13, 2017, at [[UFC 211]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com/ufc/story/henry-cejudo-vs-sergio-pettis-joins-stacked-ufc-211-line-up-030717|title=Henry Cejudo vs. Sergio Pettis joins stacked UFC 211 line up|publisher=foxsports.com|author=Damon Martin|date=March 7, 2017|accessdate=March 7, 2017}}</ref> However, on May 10, Cejudo pulled out of the fight with a hand injury and the bout was canceled.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2017/5/10/15619166/ufc-211s-sergio-pettis-vs-henry-cejudo-fight-canceled|title=UFC 211\u2019s Sergio Pettis vs. Henry Cejudo fight canceled|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Ariel Helwani|date=May 10, 2017|accessdate=May 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nCejudo faced [[Wilson Reis]] on September 9, 2017, at [[UFC 215]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.tsn.ca/reis-cejudo-and-moras-evans-smith-added-to-ufc-216-card-1.772686|title=Reis, Cejudo and Moras, Evans-Smith added to UFC 216 card|publisher=tsn.ca|author=Ken Rodney|date=June 7, 2017|accessdate=June 7, 2017}}</ref> He won the fight via TKO in the second round.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloodyelbow.com/2017/9/9/16281048/ufc-215-results-henry-cejudo-vs-wilson-reis-mma-news|title=UFC 215 results: Henry Cejudo blasts out Wilson Reis|work=Bloody Elbow|access-date=September 10, 2017}}</ref> This win also won Cejudo his first ''[[List of UFC bonus award recipients|Performance of the Night]]'' bonus award.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloodyelbow.com/2017/9/10/16282694/ufc-215-edmonton-post-fight-bonuses-henry-cejudo-jeremy-stephens-among-50k-winners|title=UFC 215 bonuses: Cejudo, Stephens among $50K winners|work=Bloody Elbow|access-date=September 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nA rescheduled fight with Pettis took place on December 2, 2017, at [[UFC 218]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2017/9/27/16376430/henry-cejudo-vs-sergio-pettis-targeted-for-ufc-218|title=Henry Cejudo vs. Sergio Pettis targeted for UFC 218|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Ariel Helwani|date=September 27, 2017|accessdate=September 27, 2017}}</ref> Cejudo won the fight by unanimous decision.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2017/12/ufc-218-results-henry-cejudo-outwrestles-sergio-pettis-for-scorecard-sweep|title=UFC 218 results: Henry Cejudo outwrestles Sergio Pettis for scorecard sweep|date=December 3, 2017|work=MMAjunkie|access-date=December 3, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n====Double UFC Champion====\nTwo years after challenging for the Flyweight title, Cejudo faced [[Demetrious Johnson (fighter)|Demetrious Johnson]] in a rematch for [[UFC Flyweight Championship]] title in the co-main event at [[UFC 227]] on August 4, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2018/6/9/17445216/demetrious-johnson-vs-henry-cejudo-2-booked-for-ufc-227|title=Demetrious Johnson vs. Henry Cejudo 2 booked for UFC 227|work=MMA Fighting|access-date=June 10, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2018/6/9/17445216/demetrious-johnson-vs-henry-cejudo-2-booked-for-ufc-227|title=Demetrious Johnson vs. Henry Cejudo 2 booked for UFC 227|work=MMA Fighting|access-date=August 6, 2018}}</ref> Cejudo went on to win the back-and-forth fight via split decision to become the UFC's second Flyweight champion and first Olympic gold medalist to capture UFC gold.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2789549-henry-cejudo-defeats-demetrius-johnson-by-split-decision-at-ufc-227|title=Henry Cejudo Defeats Demetrious Johnson by Split Decision at UFC 227|last=Ballentine|first=Alex|work=Bleacher Report|access-date=August 12, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> This fight earned him the [[List of UFC bonus award recipients|Fight of the Night]] award.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mmajunkie.com/2018/08/ufc-227-bonuses-tj-dillashaw-henry-cejudo-50000-winners-los-angeles|title=UFC 227 bonuses: Champs Dillashaw, Cejudo among $50,000 winners in Los Angeles|date=August 5, 2018|work=MMAjunkie|access-date=August 5, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> 13 of 25 media outlets scored the bout in favor of Cejudo, while 12 scored it for Johnson.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmadecisions.com/decision/9284/Henry-Cejudo-vs-Demetrious-Johnson|title=Cejudo def. Johnson |publisher=mmadecisions.com |date= August 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, Cejudo revealed that he had signed a six-fight contract with UFC.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmamania.com/2018/11/12/18088584/ufc-233-henry-cejudo-doesnt-rule-out-move-one-championship-after-stopping-tj-dillashaw-mma|title=UFC 233: Henry Cejudo doesn\u2019t rule out move to ONE Championship after stopping TJ Dillashaw |author=Adam Guillen Jr.|publisher=mmamania.com|date=November 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the first defense of his [[UFC Flyweight Championship]], Cejudo was initially scheduled to face [[UFC Bantamweight Championship|UFC Bantamweight champion]] [[T.J. Dillashaw]] on January 26, 2019, at [[UFC 233]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mmamania.com/2018/11/26/18113775/ufc-233-henry-cejudo-tj-dillashaw-flyweight-title-fight-official-jan-26-anaheim-mma|title=UFC 233: Henry Cejudo vs TJ Dillashaw flyweight title fight official for Jan. 26 in Anaheim|work=MMAmania.com|access-date=2018-11-29}}</ref> However, after that pay-per-view event was canceled, the fight was moved a week earlier to headline [[UFC Fight Night 143]] on January 19, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.com/2018/11/henry-cejudo-vs-tj-dillashaw-title-fight-official-ufc-233-anaheim|title=Henry Cejudo vs. T.J. Dillashaw flyweight title fight official for UFC 233 in Anaheim|date=2018-11-27|website=MMAjunkie|language=en|access-date=2018-12-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mmamania.com/2018/11/26/18113775/ufc-233-henry-cejudo-tj-dillashaw-flyweight-title-fight-official-jan-26-anaheim-mma|title=UFC 233: Henry Cejudo vs TJ Dillashaw flyweight title fight official for Jan. 19 in Anaheim|work=MMAmania.com|access-date=November 29, 2018}}</ref> It was the first title fight to showcase the new UFC legacy belt. Cejudo won the fight via TKO just 32 seconds into the first round to retain his title.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2019/1/20/18190221/ufc-brooklyn-results-henry-cejudo-stops-t-j-dillashaw-in-32-seconds|title=UFC Brooklyn results: Henry Cejudo stops T.J. Dillashaw in 32 seconds|website=MMAFighting.com|author=Dave Doyle|date=2019-01-20|access-date=2019-01-21}}</ref> The win also earned Cejudo his second ''Performance of the Night'' bonus award.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sherdog.com/news/news/UFC-Brooklyn-Bonuses-Donald-Cerrone-Pockets-36100K-in-Successful-Lightweight-Return-148377|title=UFC Brooklyn bonuses: Donald Cerrone pockets $100K in successful lightweight return|website=Sherdog.com|author=Tristen Critchfield|date=2019-01-20|access-date=2019-01-21}}</ref> On 9 April 2019, USADA announced that Dillashaw had tested positive for [[erythropoietin|EPO]] in pre and post-fight screenings and had been suspended for two years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.co.uk/mma/story/_/id/26479192|title=USADA suspends Dillashaw 2 years for EPO use|date=April 9, 2019|website=ESPN.com}}</ref>\n\nCejudo faced [[Marlon Moraes]] on June 8, 2019 at [[UFC 238]] for the vacant [[UFC Bantamweight Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.com/2019/03/henry-cejudo-marlon-moraes-official-ufc-238|title=Henry Cejudo vs. Marlon Moraes official for UFC 238|date=2019-03-27|website=MMA Junkie|language=en|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref> He won the fight via TKO in the third round.<ref name=\"mmajunkie1\">{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.com/2019/06/ufc-238-results-henry-cejudo-tko-marlon-moraes-second-title-history|title=UFC 238 results: Henry Cejudo TKOs Marlon Moraes to win second title|date=2019-06-09|website=MMA Junkie|language=en|access-date=2019-06-09}}</ref> This win made Cejudo the fourth fighter to hold championships simultaneously in two weight divisions in UFC, and earned him the [[List of UFC bonus award recipients|''Performance of the Night'']] award. Cejudo became inactive until 2020 due to a shoulder injury.<ref name=\"mmajunkie2\">{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.com/2019/06/ufc-238-bonuses-tony-ferguson-cowboy-cerrone-valentina-shevchenko-henry-cejudo|title=UFC 238 bonuses: Tony Ferguson, 'Cowboy' Cerrone get a clear 'Fight of Night' winner|date=2019-06-09|website=MMA Junkie|language=en|access-date=2019-06-09}}</ref>\n\nOn December 19, 2019, it was announced that Cejudo will officially relinquish the UFC Flyweight title and is focusing on the bantamweight division.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports.yahoo.com/amphtml/ufc-henry-cejudo-flyweight-title-stripped-joseph-benavidez-deiveson-figueirdo-bourt-february-040114862.html|title=Report: Henry Cejudo\u2019s belt stripped, setting up Benavidez-Deiveson title fight in February|work=Yahoo Sports|date=December 19, 2019|accessdate=December 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nCejudo was scheduled to face [[Jos\u00e9 Aldo]] on May 9, 2020 at [[UFC 250]].<ref name=\"SPHeadliner\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mma/story/_/id/28774219/jose-aldo-challenge-henry-cejudo-ufc-250-brazil|title=Jose Aldo to challenge Henry Cejudo at UFC 250 in Brazil|website=[[ESPN.com]]|author=Brett Okamoto|date=2020-02-24|access-date=2020-02-24}} </ref> However, Aldo pulled out on April 8 due to visa issues. Cejudo is expected to defend against former champion [[Dominick Cruz]].<ref name=\"cruz\">{{cite web |last1=Guillen Jr. |first1=Adam |title=Jose Aldo out of UFC 250, Dominick Cruz steps in to face Henry Cejudo for the Bantamweight title on May 9 |url=https://www.mmamania.com/2020/4/9/21214352/ufc-dominick-cruz-face-henry-cejudo-bantamweight-title-ufc-250-jose-aldo-out-espn-mma |website=mmamania.com |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> However, on April 9, [[Dana White]], the president of UFC announced that this event was postponed to a future date<ref name=\"Postpone\">{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mma/story/_/id/29018339/dana-white-says-ufc-249-not-happen-april-18|title=Dana White says UFC 249 will not happen April 18|publisher=espn.com|author=Brett Okamoto|date=2020-04-09|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Championships and achievements==\n*'''[[Ultimate Fighting Championship]]'''\n**[[UFC Bantamweight Championship]] (One time, current)<ref name=\"mmajunkie1\"/>\n**[[List of UFC Champions#Flyweight Championship|UFC Flyweight Championship]] (One time)\n***One successful title defense\n**Seventh multi-divisional champion in UFC history\n**Fourth simultaneous multi-divisional champion\n**[[Bonus Awards|Fight of the Night]] (One time) {{small| vs. [[Demetrious Johnson (fighter)|Demetrious Johnson]]}}\n**[[Bonus Awards|Performance of the Night]] (Three times) {{small| vs. [[Wilson Reis]], [[T.J. Dillashaw]], and [[Marlon Moraes]]}}<ref name=\"mmajunkie2\"/>\n*'''[[MMAjunkie.com|MMAjunkie]]'''\n** 2018 Upset of the Year <small>vs. [[Demetrious Johnson (fighter)|Demetrious Johnson]]</small><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.com/2019/01/mmajunkie-2018-upset-of-year-cejudo-dethrones-demetrious-johnson-ufc-227|title=MMAjunkie's 2018 'Upset of the Year': Henry Cejudo dethrones mighty Demetrious Johnson|author=Steven Marrocco|date=January 2, 2019|publisher=mmajunkie.com}}</ref>\n** 2019 June Fight of the Month <small>vs. [[Marlon Moraes]]</small><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.com/2019/07/fight-of-the-month-june-2019-henry-cejudo-marlon-moraes-ufc-238|title=MMA Junkie's 'Fight of the Month' for June: A wild comeback with historic consequences|date=July 3, 2019|publisher=mmajunkie.com}}</ref>\n*'''[[MMA Fighting]]'''\n** 2018 Upset of the Year <small>vs. [[Demetrious Johnson (fighter)|Demetrious Johnson]]</small><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2019/1/6/18164649/mma-fightings-2018-upset-of-the-year-henry-cejudo-ends-demetrious-johnsons-epic-reign|title=MMA Fighting\u2019s 2018 Upset of the Year: Henry Cejudo ends Demetrious Johnson\u2019s epic reign |author=Mike Chiappetta|date=January 6, 2019|publisher=mmafighting.com}}</ref>\n*'''[[SB Nation|MMA Weekly]]'''\n** 2018 Upset of the Year <small>vs. [[Demetrious Johnson (fighter)|Demetrious Johnson]]</small><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmaweekly.com/2018-upset-of-the-year-henry-cejudos-win-over-demetrious-johnson|title=2018 Upset of the Year: Henry Cejudo\u2019s Win Over Demetrious Johnson|author=Jeff Cain|date=January 11, 2019|publisher=mmaweekly.com}}</ref>\n*'''MMADNA.nl'''\n**2018 Upset of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmadna.nl/mma-dna-ufc-awards-2018-de-uitslagen/|title=MMA DNA UFC Awards 2018 : De Uitslagen!!!|last=DNA|first=MMA|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-28}}</ref>\n\n==Mixed martial arts record==\n{{MMArecordbox\n| ko-wins=7\n| sub-wins=\n| dec-wins=8\n| ko-losses=1\n| sub-losses=\n| dec-losses=1\n}}\n{{MMA record start}}\n|-\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|align=center|15\u20132\n|[[Marlon Moraes]]\n|TKO (punches)\n|[[UFC 238]] \n|{{dts|2019|June|8}}\n|align=center|3\n|align=center|4:51\n|[[Chicago, Illinois]], United States\n|{{small|Won the vacant [[UFC Bantamweight Championship]]. Performance of the Night.}}\n|-\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|align=center|14\u20132\n|[[T.J. Dillashaw]]\n|TKO (punches)\n|[[UFC Fight Night: Cejudo vs. Dillashaw]]\n|{{dts|2019|January|19|format=mdy}}\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|0:32\n|[[Brooklyn, New York]], United States\n|{{small|Defended the [[UFC Flyweight Championship]]. Performance of the Night. Dillashaw tested positive in pre and post-fight drug tests for [[erythropoietin]] (EPO). Vacated the title on December 19, 2019.}}\n|-\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|align=center|13\u20132\n|[[Demetrious Johnson]]\n|Decision (split)\n|[[UFC 227]] \n|{{dts|2018|August|4|format=mdy}}\n|align=center|5\n|align=center|5:00\n|[[Los Angeles, California]], United States\n|{{small|Won the [[UFC Flyweight Championship]]. Fight of the Night.}} \n|-\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|align=center|1