he \u20a41,000 Pyramid Game]]\n| rowspan=2|Steve Jones\n| rowspan=2|[[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]\n| 1981\u201384\n|-\n| [[The Pyramid Game]]'''\n| 1989\u201390\n|-\n| [[The Pyramid Game|Donny's Pyramid Game]]\n| [[Donny Osmond]]\n| [[Challenge TV|Challenge]]\n| 2007\n|-\n|rowspan=2 |{{Flag|Venezuela}}\n| Match 4\n| Juan Manuel Montesinos\n| Venevisi\u03ccn\n| 1984\u201389\n|-\n| Contra reloj\n| [[Daniela Kos\u00e1n]]\n| [[Televen]]\n| 2001\u201302\n|-\n| {{Flag|Vietnam}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=g_bsNSY0AqU|title=[ HTV7 ] - Gameshow KIm|accessdate=28 January 2019|publisher=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>\n| Kim t\u1ef1 th\u00e1p\n| [[:vi:Chi B\u1ea3o|Chi B\u1ea3o]] [[:vi:Kids Thi\u00ean B\u1ea3o|Thi\u00ean B\u1ea3o]]\n| HTV7\n| April 30, 2005 \u2013 2007\n|}\n\nThe British version was called ''[[The Pyramid Game]]'' and ran intermittently from 1981 to 1990, with [[Steve Jones (game show presenter)|Steve Jones]] as host. Donny Osmond hosted a short-lived 2007 revival, which used a similar set and the same music package as the 2002 American revival hosted by Osmond.\n\nIn 2009, Sony created an Australian version of ''The Junior Partner Pyramid'' called simply ''[[Pyramid (Australian game show)|Pyramid]]''. This version was hosted by [[Shura Taft]] until 2012, with Graham Matters taking over the following year.\n\nA German version titled ''[[:de:Die Pyramide (Fernsehsendung)|Die Pyramide]]'' aired on [[ZDF]] from 1979 to 1994, and was hosted by [[Dieter Thomas Heck]]. A new version aired on [[ZDFneo]] in 2012, and was co-hosted by [[:de:Micky Beisenherz|Micky Beisenherz]] and [[:de:Joachim Llambi|Joachim Llambi]].\n\nVersions in French, both titled ''[[:fr:Pyramide (jeu t\u00e9l\u00e9vis\u00e9)|Pyramide]]'', were produced at different times in France and in Canada.\n\n==Home games==\nThe first [[board game]] of ''The $10,000 Pyramid'' was released in 1974 by the [[Milton Bradley Company]], with a total of eight editions produced through 1981. Beginning with the fourth edition, like its TV counterpart, the title and top payoff changed to ''The $20,000 Pyramid'', while the final edition was titled ''The $50,000 Pyramid''. However, due to concerns about players easily memorizing possible Winners' Circle subjects, the format of the board game's Winners' Circle endgame was changed to mirror that of the TV version's main game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://legendsrevealed.com/entertainment/2015/06/08/why-did-the-board-game-version-of-the-25000-pyramid-not-actually-have-a-pyramid-in-it/|title=Why Did the Board Game Version of the $25,000 Pyramid Not Actually Have a Pyramid In It?|date=8 June 2015|website=Legendsrevealed.com|accessdate=28 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nCardinal Games released a new home version of ''The $25,000 Pyramid'' in 1986,<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/Pyramid-Board-Game-1986-Clark/dp/B001TKV6WG] {{dead link|date=January 2019}}</ref> this time using the actual Winners' Circle rules and format, which was also given to all contestants who appeared on both the daytime and nighttime versions for most of 1987. This version was reissued in 2000 by Endless Games,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boardgamegeek.com/boardgameversion/102389/endless-edition-2000|title=The $25,000 Pyramid Game (Endless edition 2000) - Board Game Version - BoardGameGeek|website=Boardgamegeek.com|accessdate=28 January 2019}}</ref> which later released a new edition based on the Osmond version in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geekyhobbies.com/pyramid-home-game-board-game-review-and-rules/|title=Pyramid: Home Game Series Board Game Review and Rules|first=Eric|last=Mortensen|date=1 August 2017|website=Geekyhobbies.com|accessdate=28 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n''The $100,000 Pyramid'', a [[video game]] adaptation, was released in 1987. Developed and published by Box Office Software, it was originally released for [[Apple II]] and then ported to [[DOS]] and [[Commodore 64]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mobygames.com/game/100000-pyramid_|title=The $100,000 Pyramid for Apple II (1987)|website=MobyGames|accessdate=28 January 2019}}</ref> Years later, [[Sierra Attractions]] released a new [[PC CD-ROM]] version of ''The $100,000 Pyramid'' in 2001,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/games/the-100000-pyramid|title=The $100,000 Pyramid |accessdate=28 January 2019|website=Ign.com}}</ref> which was followed by a [[DVD game]] from [[MGA Entertainment]] in 2006.\n\nA version titled ''The $1,000,000 Pyramid'' was released by [[Ubisoft]] for the [[Nintendo Wii]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/games/the-1000000-pyramid|title=The $1,000,000 Pyramid|website=Ign.com|accessdate=28 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\t\n* {{cite book|url=https://www.amazon.com/Encyclopedia-TV-Game-Shows/dp/0816038473|last1=Schwartz|first1=David|last2=Ryan|first2=Steve|last3=Wostbrock|first3=Fred|title=The Encyclopedia of TV Game Shows|edition=3rd|year=1999|publisher=Checkmark Books|location=[[New York City]]|isbn=978-0816038473|pages=220\u2013222}}\n* {{cite book|url=http://www.thriftbooks.com/w/come-on-down-the-tv-game-show-book_jefferson-graham/497471#isbn=0896597946|last=Graham|first=Jefferson|title=Come on Down the TV Game Show Book|publisher=[[Abbeville Publishing Group|Abbeville Press]]|year=1988|pages=181\u2013182|location=[[New York City]]|isbn=0-89659-794-6}}\t\n* {{cite book|url=http://www.abebooks.com/servlet/BookDetailsPL?bi=268930272&searchurl=tn%3Dtv%2520game%2520shows%2520a%2520behind%2520the%2520screen%2520look%2520at%2520the%2520stars%2520the%2520prizes%2520the%2520hosts%2520the%2520scandals%26sortby%3D17%26an%3Dfabe%2520maxene|last=Fabe|first=Maxene|title=TV Game Shows! A Behind-The-Screen Look At The Stars! The Prizes! The Hosts! And The Scandals!|publisher=[[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday & Co.]]|year=1979|pages=255\u2013259|location=[[New York City]]|isbn=978-0385130523}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://abc.go.com/shows/the-100000-pyramid}} (ABC, 2016)\n*{{Official website|https://web.archive.org/web/20120930231842/http://gsntv.com/shows/the-pyramid/}} (GSN, at the [[Wayback Machine]])\n*{{IMDb title|185049|The (New) $25,000 Pyramid}} 1982\u201387/1988 US Version\n*{{IMDb title|324893|Pyramid}} 2002\u201304 US Version\n*{{IMDb title|2266944|The Pyramid}} 2012 US Version\n*{{IMDb title|5330088|The $100,000 Pyramid}} 2016 US Version\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach}}\n{{succession box | before = ''[[Hollywood Squares]]'' | title = [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Game/Audience Participation Show]] | years = 1976<br />as ''The $20,000 Pyramid'' | after = ''[[Family Feud]]''}}\n{{succession box | before = ''[[Hollywood Squares]]'' | title = [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Game/Audience Participation Show]] | years = 1980\u201381<br />as ''The $20,000 Pyramid''<br />tie with ''[[Hollywood Squares]]'' in 1980 | after = ''[[Password Plus and Super Password|Password Plus]]''}}\n{{succession box | before = ''[[Password Plus and Super Password|Password Plus]]'' | title = [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Game/Audience Participation Show]]| years = 1983\u201387<br />as ''The $25,000 Pyramid'' | after = ''[[The Price Is Right (U.S. game show)|The Price Is Right]]''}}\n{{succession box | before = ''[[The Price Is Right (U.S. game show)|The Price Is Right]]'' | title = [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Game/Audience Participation Show]] | years = 1989<br />as ''The $25,000 Pyramid'' | after = ''[[Jeopardy!]]''}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Daytime Emmy Award Outstanding Game/Audience Participation Show}}\n{{ABCNetwork Shows (current and upcoming)}}\n{{Game Show Network}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pyramid}}\n[[Category:1970s American game shows]]\n[[Category:1973 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1980 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:1980s American game shows]]\n[[Category:1981 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1981 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:1988 Ameri