ana, 1st Class]]\n[[Category:Syracuse University College of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:United States senators from Delaware]]\n[[Category:University of Delaware alumni]]\n[[Category:Vice Presidents of the United States]]\n[[Category:Widener University faculty]]\n[[Category:Recipients of Hilal-i-Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Chairmen of the Senate Committee on Foreign Relations]]\n", "name_user": "Thanoscar21", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor grammar edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joe_Biden"}
{"title_page": "Kajal Bandyopadhyay", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer  \n| name          = Kajal Bandyopadhyay\n| image         = \n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| pseudonym     = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1954|02|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Barisal]], [[East Bengal]], [[Dominion of Pakistan]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place   = \n| resting_place = \n| occupation    = Writer, professor, poet, translator\n| language      = [[Bengali language|Bengali]],  [[English language|English]]\n| nationality   = [[Bangladeshi]]\n| ethnicity     = \n| citizenship   = \n| education     =\n| years_active  =\n| alma_mater    = \n| period        = \n| genre         = \n| subject       = \n| movement      = \n| notableworks  = \n| awards        =  \n}}\n\n'''Kajal Bandyopadhyay''' (born 13 February 1954<ref name=\"Poet's idea\">{{cite news |title=A poet's ideas on Female Power |url=https://dailyasianage.com/news/68464/a-poets-ideas-on-female-power |newspaper=[[Daily Asian Age]] |language=English|date=17 June 2017 |accessdate=29 April 2018}}</ref>) is a Bangladeshi poet, writer, and translator.<ref name=\"Bangla Academy Dictionary of Writers\">{{cite book|title=Bangla Academy Dictionary of Writers|year=2000|publisher=[[Bangla Academy]]|location=[[Dhaka]]|isbn=984-07-4052-0|pages=95\u201396|editor=[[Selina Hossain]], Nurul Islam and Mobarak Hossain}}</ref> He teaches [[English literature]] and currently working as head of the dept. of English at the [[University of Dhaka]].\n\n== Teaching career ==\nBandyopadhyay graduated from the University of Dhaka and completed his Ph.D. from [[Jadavpur University]], Calcutta on [[Wole Soyinka]].<ref name=\"Bangla Academy Dictionary of Writers\"/>\n\n== Literature ==\nAs a Marxist poet, Bandyopadhyay vividly portrays the \"lives of toiling masses, particularly their problems, social conflicts, intrigues and inner complexes\" with poignant poetic expressions.<ref name=\"Bangla Academy Dictionary of Writers\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=All about sexual, textual politics |url=http://archive.thedailystar.net/newDesign/news-details.php?nid=3990 |newspaper=The Daily Star |accessdate=27 November 2013}}</ref>  A presidium member of Bangladesh Hindu Buddhist Christian Unity Council, Bandyopadhyay is also a vehement activist against communal violence in Bangladesh. He champions secularism and non-[[Communalism (South Asia)|communalism]] in Bangladesh; to protest attacks on minority communities in Bangladesh, he wanted to receive self-imprisonment in 2013.<ref>{{cite news |date=24 April 2013|title=DU teacher offers to be in jail|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/beta2/news/du-teacher-offers-to-be-in-jail/ |newspaper=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]] |accessdate=27 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=24 April 2013 |script-title=bn:\u09b8\u09be\u09ae\u09cd\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a6\u09be\u09af\u09bc\u09bf\u0995 \u09b8\u09b9\u09bf\u0982\u09b8\u09a4\u09be \u0985\u09ac\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09b9\u09a4: \u09b8\u09cd\u09ac\u09c7\u099a\u09cd\u099b\u09be\u09af\u09bc \u0995\u09be\u09b0\u09be\u09ac\u09b0\u09a3 \u0995\u09b0\u09a4\u09c7 \u099a\u09be\u09a8 \u0985\u09a7\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09aa\u0995 \u0995\u09be\u099c\u09b2 \u09ac\u09a8\u09cd\u09a6\u09cd\u09af\u09cb\u09aa\u09be\u09a7\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09af\u09bc |url=http://www.thedailysangbad.com/index.php?ref=MjBfMDNfMjRfMTNfMV8xM18xXzEyOTYzNQ== |newspaper=[[The Sangbad]] |language=Bengali |accessdate=27 November 2013 |title=Archived copy |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203042738/http://www.thedailysangbad.com/index.php?ref=MjBfMDNfMjRfMTNfMV8xM18xXzEyOTYzNQ== |archive-date=3 December 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nProfessor Bandyopadhyay's \u201cessays speak of establishing a plural and classless society. They also unveil religious orthodoxy and fanaticism, and bring out the causes of cultural imperialism.\u201d<ref>{{cite news |date=11 October 2018|title=Looking through the progressive lens|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/magazine/arts-letters/2018/10/11/looking-through-the-progressive-lens |newspaper=[[The Dhaka Tribune (Bangladesh)|The Dhaka Tribune]] |accessdate=9 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Interest on African literature ===\nKajal Banerjee has an especial fascination for African literature. He did his Ph.D. on the plays of [[Nobel Prize|Noble laureate]] African writer [[Wole Soyinka]]. Some books of his essays on African literature in English and Ibsen's plays have been received warmly.<ref name=\"Poet's idea\"/>\n\n==Selected publications<ref name=\"Bangla Academy Dictionary of Writers\"/>==\n=== Books of Bengali poems ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Publishers !! First Published\n|-\n| ''Hameshai Danober Trankorta-Besh'' ||  || \n|-\n| ''Kangal Deerghokal'' (Seeker for a Long Time) ||  || 1985\n|-\n| ''Dagdha Dhoolikona'' (Burnt-out Speck) ||  || 1986\n|-\n| ''Prithibir Grihakone'' (In a Home of the Earth) ||  || 1988\n|-\n| ''Utthaner Mantra Nei'' (No Chant to Rise) ||  || 1989\n|-\n| ''Heshe Othe Ashrujol'' (Tears smiles) ||  || 1998\n|-\n| ''Unoswad Unouchcharon'' ||  || \n|-\n| ''Phulo Unmatto Rangeen'' ||  ||\n|-\n| ''Tritiya Bishwer Kobita'' (Poems of the Third World) ||  || 1998\n|-\n| ''Protiprem, Proti-Akhyan'' || Ananya || 2017\n|}\n\n=== Essay ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Publishers !! First Published\n|-\n| ''Swapna'' (Dream) ||  || 1985\n|-\n| ''Samrajyobad: Onya Unmochan'' (Imperialism: Other Exposures) || [[Bangla Academy]] || 1986\n|-\n| ''Katha Kalantorer, Pragotir'' || Jatio Grantho Prokashon || 2009\n|-\n| ''Pragati Sahitya Katipoy Tattwo Bichar'' || Nandyonik || 2011\n|-\n| ''Rabindranath: Dharmobhabna'' || Moordhanyo || 2012\n|-\n| ''Tension and  Syntheses in Wole Soyinka's Plays'' || [[Dhaka University Press]] || 5 August 2012\n|-\n| ''Female Power And Some Ibsen Plays'' || Moordhanyo || 2015\n|}\n\n=== Edited Bibliography ===\n\n{| cla