9a\u09cd\u099b\u09be\u09af\u09bc \u0995\u09be\u09b0\u09be\u09ac\u09b0\u09a3 \u0995\u09b0\u09a4\u09c7 \u099a\u09be\u09a8 \u0985\u09a7\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09aa\u0995 \u0995\u09be\u099c\u09b2 \u09ac\u09a8\u09cd\u09a6\u09cd\u09af\u09cb\u09aa\u09be\u09a7\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09af\u09bc |url=http://www.thedailysangbad.com/index.php?ref=MjBfMDNfMjRfMTNfMV8xM18xXzEyOTYzNQ== |newspaper=[[The Sangbad]] |language=Bengali |accessdate=27 November 2013 |title=Archived copy |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203042738/http://www.thedailysangbad.com/index.php?ref=MjBfMDNfMjRfMTNfMV8xM18xXzEyOTYzNQ== |archive-date=3 December 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nProfessor Bandyopadhyay's \u201cessays speak of establishing a plural and classless society. They also unveil religious orthodoxy and fanaticism, and bring out the causes of cultural imperialism.\u201d<ref>{{cite news |date=11 October 2018|title=Looking through the progressive lens|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/magazine/arts-letters/2018/10/11/looking-through-the-progressive-lens |newspaper=[[The Dhaka Tribune (Bangladesh)|The Dhaka Tribune]] |accessdate=9 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Interest on African literature ===\nKajal Banerjee has an especial fascination for African literature. He did his Ph.D. on the plays of [[Nobel Prize|Noble laureate]] African writer [[Wole Soyinka]]. Some books of his essays on African literature in English and Ibsen's plays have been received warmly.<ref name=\"Poet's idea\"/>\n\n==Selected publications<ref name=\"Bangla Academy Dictionary of Writers\"/>==\n=== Books of Bengali poems ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Publishers !! First Published\n|-\n| ''Hameshai Danober Trankorta-Besh'' ||  || \n|-\n| ''Kangal Deerghokal'' (Seeker for a Long Time) ||  || 1985\n|-\n| ''Dagdha Dhoolikona'' (Burnt-out Speck) ||  || 1986\n|-\n| ''Prithibir Grihakone'' (In a Home of the Earth) ||  || 1988\n|-\n| ''Utthaner Mantra Nei'' (No Chant to Rise) ||  || 1989\n|-\n| ''Heshe Othe Ashrujol'